<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     10-20 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Thaw Between Rival Black Groups Following Prisoner Release</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The release of seven African
Congress National leaders from prison has been welcomed in black
townships nationwide, but there is no sign of a thaw between the
guerrilla group and its black political rivals.
   Mangosuthu Buthelezi, the most powerful black moderate in South
Africa, complained the ANC wants to project itself as the sole
representative of the country's blacks.
   ``I shudder to think what would happen to South Africa if we all
stood aside and allowed only one black party to negotiate the
future with the government,'' Buthelezi said Thursday.
   Buthelezi, a critic of the ANC's socialist ideology and its
bombing and sabotage campaign, is chief minister of the tribal
homeland of KwaZulu. He also is leader of Inkatha, a Zulu
organization that claims 1.5 million members and which has feuded
violently in the past three years with supporters of the ANC.
   More than 2,000 blacks in Natal Province have died in the
conflict, and recent efforts to promote peace talks have collapsed.
   Also remaining at odds with the ANC is the outlawed Pan
Africanist Congress. Both groups have conducted guerrilla
operations against the government in the past three decades, but
the Pan Africanist Congress is smaller, has been less active and
has sharp ideological differences with the ANC.
   The ANC follows a policy of non-racialism and welcomes whites in
its ranks. The Pan Africanist Congress espouses the ``black
consciousness'' philosophy pioneered by Steve Biko before his death
in detention in 1977, and believes whites should have no role in
the struggle for black rights.
   One Pan Africanist Congress member, Jafta Masemola, was released
from prison Oct. 14 along with the seven ANC leaders. But he stayed
out of the spotlight at his home near Pretoria while the ANC men
held a triumphant news conference that was covered by journalists
from around the world.
   In subsequent interviews, Masemola, 60, said he foresaw no
likelihood of his group and the ANC uniting. Unlike the ANC
leaders, he said there was no purpose in pursuing negotiations with
the government, calling them ``an exercise in futility'' because
the ruling National Party would not negotiate itself out of power.
   The leader of the Pan Africanist Congress, Zeph Mothopeng, was
freed from prison last year. He met during the week with Walter
Sisulu, the most senior of the freed ANC prisoners, but has given
no indication of an ideological rapprochement between the two
groups.
   Earlier this month, Mothopeng even criticized the campaign of
protest marches organized by anti-apartheid groups aligned with the
ANC.
   He said President F.W. de Klerk had gained favorable publicity
overseas by allowing the marches, and asked: ``How much closer to
liberation did they bring the oppressed?''
   Both Mothopeng and Buthelezi have sought to avoid portraying
themselves as personal rivals of Nelson Mandela, the paramount ANC
leader who remains in jail. Buthelezi has depicted Mandela as his
friend and said repeatedly that he will not enter political
negotiations with the government until Mandela is freed.
</TEXT>
