<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kathrine is cq in second item</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wealthy businessman Del Dunmire has
given hundreds of thousands in donations over the years, but his
$50,000 gift to the city of Abilene, Kan., had a special meaning.
   In 1958, Dunmire robbed the Commercial State Bank in Abilene.
   He was caught, convicted and sent to prison, serving two years
before being paroled. After his release, Dunmire borrowed $3,000 to
start Growth Industries, the aviation parts company that became the
source of his wealth.
   The gift to Abilene will help rebuild a bandstand destroyed by
fire.
   The robbery 31 years ago netted Dunmire $2,261.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kathrine Rice strutted slowly down the runway at a
charity fashion show, sashaying this way and that to show off the
white beaded-lace sheath she wore.
   But the once-aspiring actress demurred when anyone suggested
that at age 95, she looked radiantly beautiful.
   ``I was just doing my job. The dress did a lot,'' said Rice, who
dispatches questions about her marital status with a snappy: ``Just
plain Rice, never married.''
   Rice was among a bevy of models over 40 who presented evening
wear and furs at a fund-raiser Friday for Reading is Fundamental, a
non-profit organization.
   Rice said that years ago she planned a career on the stage and
played bit parts in the Provincetown Players on Cape Cod, which
gave playwright Eugene O'Neill his start.
   She got a toehold in the pictures, playing extras. But other
obligations brought down the curtain on those dreams and she
returned to Boston to help in the family tie-manufacturing business.
   Friday she returned to the spotlight.
   Her thoughts? ``I was nervous.''
