<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Axl Rose, lead singer of the rock group Guns
N' Roses, apologized on stage for telling a concert audience he was
quitting the band.
   Guns N' Roses is booked as the opening act for the Rolling
Stones' four Los Angeles concerts, with the last two perfomances
scheduled for tonight and Sunday. Rose made the apology Thursday at
the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum after complaining out loud on
stage Wednesday that he was going to quit because of excessive drug
use in the group.
   ``I just didn't want to see my friends slip away,'' Rose
explained.
   The Los Angeles band, which has sold more than 12 million albums
in the last two years, has fueled controversy over its use of
racial and sexual slurs on its record ``One in A Million.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neil Armstrong, the first man to walk on
the moon, is joining the board of directors of Thiokol Corp., whose
rocket was blamed in the 1986 explosion of the space shuttle
Challenger.
   Armstrong and several other directors were elected Thursday in
the first shareholders' meeting of the company since the separation
of Morton Thiokol Inc. into Thiokol and Morton International Inc.
in July.
   The explosion of Challenger was blamed on a faulty O-ring seal
on one of the shuttle's solid-fuel booster rockets, which were
built by Morton Thiokol. Seven astronauts died in the explosion.
   Thiokol was involved in the redesign of the rockets and since
the redesign there have been six successful missions, U. Edwin
Garrison, chief executive officer of the company, told shareholders.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Pennsylvania's Wharton
School has replaced the photograph of indicted junk bond financier
Michael Milken that was stolen earlier this month from an exhibit
called the Alumni Honor Roll.
   Officials of the business school replaced the plaque Friday
without ceremony,Wharton spokeswoman Denise Portner said.
   The Milken photograph, together with 17 other picture-plaques,
will remain until students vote at an unspecified date on a new
group of alumni to replace those chosen in 1986.
   Among alumni now honored are entrepreneur Donald Trump, media
magnate Walter Annenberg, Supreme Court Justice William Brennan,
CBS founder William Paley, John Sculley of Apple computers, Robert
Crandall of American Airlines, and beer tycoon August Busch III.
   Milken was indicted in March on 98 counts of racketeering and
fraud in connection with his activities with the Wall Street
investment firm of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., where he headed the
junk bond division. He has pleaded innocent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Tibbets said he had a job to do
Aug. 6, 1945, when he dropped the first atomic bomb in battle.
   And if he had to, he would do it again.
   ``Nothing like regret ever entered my mind,'' said Tibbets,
pilot of the Enola Gay. ``It was something that we were supposed to
do to defeat the enemy. That was the name of the game.''
   The bomb dropped on Hiroshima killed or injured 160,000, but
Tibbets said the loss of life would have been much greater if the
United States had been forced to invade the Japanese mainland.
   ``The Japanese would have resisted an invasion with every man,
woman and child,'' Tibbets said Thursday. ``If necessary, they
would have used sticks and stones in defense. It would have been
bloody beyond imagination.''
   Tibbetts, a 74-year-old retired brigadier general, was here for
a reunion of his old Army Air Corps outfit, the 97th Bomb Group.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor W. Wilson Goode's complaints of head
and neck pain weren't the result of a heart ailment and may have
been caused by sinus problems or something he ate, his doctor said.
   Goode, 51, was taken to the emergency room at Lankenau Hospital
early Friday by police officers stationed outside his home. He had
experienced a ``very vague discomfort in his head and neck,''
according to Dr. Arthur Whereat, who said the symptoms lasted about
15 minutes. The doctor said he planned to keep the mayor in the
hospital overnight.
   ``Mayor Goode has a perfectly normal heart and perfectly normal
coronary arteries,'' Whereat said. ``I have told him he can go back
to playing basketball or whatever he likes.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sister Isolina Ferre, a 75-year-old Roman
Catholic missionary, won the $10,000 Albert Schweitzer Prize for
Humanitarianism for her work with the poor in Appalachia, New York
and Puerto Rico.
   ``Over the years, in Puerto Rico, in Appalachia, in the Navy
Yard section of Brooklyn, I had come to realize that violence among
youth or in neighborhoods had an important relationship to family,
community, and employment,'' Ferre said after receiving the award
Friday. ``If family and community could be strengthened, and
meaningful employment made available, I was convinced that we might
make substantial progress in the struggle against neighborhood
crime and violence.''
   Ferre mediated between black and Puerto Rican youth gangs and
New York's juvenile justice system in the late 1950s and 1960s.
   In 1969, she returned to her native Puerto Rico where she
founded a community-based youth training program.
   The prize, established in 1986, is named for the Alsatian
medical missionary, theologian and musician, Dr. Albert Schweitzer
(1875-1965) and is administered by The Johns Hopkins University.
