<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 0041EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Gingrich-Ethics Bjt   10-21 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gingrich-Ethics, Bjt,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigator Said to Find No Grounds for Further Gingrich Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A preliminary investigation of Rep. Newt
Gingrich is nearing its end with an apparent conclusion by an
outside attorney that there are no grounds for a full-fledged
ethics probe of the No. 2 House Republican leader, Capitol Hill
sources say.
   But the final answer on whether the Georgia Republican is off
the hook on ethics charges will await the outcome of some ``loose
ends,'' which will be looked into by the House ethics committee's
own staff investigators.
   Chicago attorney William Kunkle, representing the firm hired as
outside counsel to look into the Gingrich matter, completed a
three-month, $150,000 investigation and gave his findings to the
Committee on Standards of Official Conduct on Wednesday, the
sources said.
   The panel could act on Gingrich's case as early as its expected
meeting next week.
   But Democratic and Republican sources, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said Kunkle also gave the panel questions that remained
unanswered and will have to be pursued by the committee's own staff
before final disposition of the case.
   One source said some of the questions could be important,
adding: ``There's a lot of loose money out there. It will be a
close call'' on whether to drop the case.
   Some of the questions involve what was done by the publisher to
promote sales of a book Gingrich wrote, ``Window of Opportunity,''
one source said.
   Kunkle is a partner in Phelan, Pope and John, the same Chicago
law firm that investigated former House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas. Wright resigned May 31. Gingrich filed the complaint that
led to the opening of Wright's ethics case, and has said his
current problems are the result of Democratic vindictiveness rather
than any wrongdoing on his part.
   Gingrich said Friday he did not know what was in the report, but
he called for it to be released publicly. He also said he had not
been contacted by the ethics committee.
   ``I haven't seen it. We have no idea what it says and we're
waiting for the committee to finish its work and we'll continue to
cooperate with the committee,'' Gingrich said. ``When it's all
done, I'm sure they will release it.''
   Gingrich is the minority whip, the second-ranking post in the
House Republican leadership.
   The case stems from a complaint by Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark.,
that Gingrich violated House rules and federal campaign finance
laws with a limited partnership created in 1984 to promote the
book, which Gingrich wrote with his wife and another co-author.
   Alexander's complaint focuses on a partnership of 21 individuals
who each put up to $5,000 to promote the book. Gingrich was not an
investor, but his wife was paid more than $10,000 for running the
partnership.
   The complaint contended the $105,000 raised by the partnership
could be considered income to Gingrich, in violation of House
limits on members' outside earnings. If not income, the complaint
said, it could be a gift to Gingrich, in violation of House rules
that prohibit members from accepting gifts worth more than $100
from anyone with a direct interest in legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
