<DOCNO> AP891021-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 0024EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SFQuake-Highway     10-21 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Highway,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Says Reports of I-880 Problems Were No Cause For Alarm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of problems noted by inspectors
of an Oakland freeway over the years gave no hint of its disastrous
collapse during a major earthquake, a top California transportation
official contends.
   The periodic maintenance and repair reports described a sagging
deck, cracks, flaking concrete, bent spans, a cracked girder and
other problems since the Cypress viaduct opened in 1957.
   But the reports on the double-deck Nimitz freeway section that
collapsed and crushed dozens of drivers were ``no cause for
alarm,'' Caltrans chief engineer Bill Schaefer said Friday. ``The
maintenance reports are not unusual at all.''
   Caltrans structures chief Jim Roberts made similar remarks at a
news conference, saying, ``I don't think it's fraught with any more
(problems)...Bridges grow old like we do.''
   ``I wouldn't leave that thing open if I thought it was unsafe,''
said Roberts, who was driving on the Interstate 880 section the day
before its top deck crashed onto the bottom deck.
   Roberts also insisted it was a lack of technology and not a lack
of money that led to delays in earthquake safety improvements on
I-880 and similar elevated roads supported by ``outrigger'' columns
on either side.
   He also said the collapse of the freeway and the damage to two
other two-tiered roads in San Francisco doesn't mean Caltrans
should stop building such structures. He said use of new technology
can ensure safety.
   The three _ I-880, the Embarcadero and I-280 _ were the only
double-deck freeways in Northern California, and all were closed by
the quake.
   Roberts also said it's not the Caltrans policy to make easy
repairs first to quake-threatened roads, adding, ``The worst case
is being fixed first.'' And he repeated that the 1\-mile-long
section of freeway that collapsed had not been viewed as a hazard.
   Caltrans has spent $54 million on first-stage earthquake safety
improvements, mainly to tie roadways to support columns, and is
spending an additional $64 million on second-stage improvements to
strengthen vertical columns, but the plan doesn't include the
Nimitz freeway or other ``multi-columned'' freeways because they
were considered safe.
   Roberts said the third-stage work, which involves strengthening
double-column supports, will have to include roads such as the
Nimitz. He said the third-phase cost could run as high as $300
million, and research under way on how to fix double-column
structures will be speeded up.
   He added that the cost of replacing the Nimitz Freeway section
could range from $50 million to $100 million, once it's demolished.
   Schaefer and Roberts also questioned various statements from
outside engineers who have said I-880 had an outdated design and
was vulnerable to quakes.
   ``You can talk to 100 engineers and get 100 different answers,''
said Schaefer. Roberts added, ``We can armchair quarterback
everything we do, let's face it.''
   Asked whether the fill land beneath the Nimitz was too soft,
Roberts said, ``I don't think you can say the land is so unstable
you can't build a bridge there.'' Reports made available Friday by
Caltrans showed top layers of fill and rubble over soft clay and
gravel.
   Another report, produced in 1982 by the state Department of
Mines and Geology said, in part: ``The elevated section through
downtown Oakland is expected to be extensively damaged.
Liquefaction and related ground failures will occur'' in a quake
with a magnitude of 8.3 on the Richter scale of ground motion.
   Tuesday's earthquake registered at 6.9.
   ``The hydraulic fills used to construct miles of freeway along
the east shore of (San Francisco Bay) in Alameda County may liquefy
during heavy shaking, with long sections becoming totally
impassable,'' said the report to the Governor's Emergency Task
Force on Earthquake Preparedness.
   ``Of course, the soils had a lot to do with the collapse,'' said
John Kariotis, one of the engineers offering criticism Friday. ``Go
back and look at pictures of Oakland in 1916. It was all marsh that
was filled in.''
   Kariotis, a South Pasadena expert on earthquake effects, and San
Francisco engineer Loring Wyllie, in San Francisco, also said that
if I-880's columns had been girded in steel and addtional concrete,
the elevated section probably would not have collapsed.
   The collapse was ``an unfortunate combination of an old
structure on soft ground,'' said Ian Buckle, the prominent
structural engineer who was named by Gov. Deukmejian to chair a
special panel reviewing the I-880 disaster. ``I'm not surprised
given the earthquake. We know those column of these old structures
are vulnerable.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
