<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 0050EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-LuckyDispatchers     10-21 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Lucky Dispatchers,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emergency Center Was Refitted Just Minutes Before Quake Hit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   County communications technicians had
just completed installing new computerized emergency radio
equipment when the earthquake struck, officials said.
   ``They had just become operable, I mean we're just talking a
matter of minutes,'' Carol England, communications supervisor for
the county, said Friday.
   The dispatch center is in the basement of the Santa Cruz county
governmental center. It serves as the nerve center for
law-enforcement, medical and fire emergencies as well as public
works and other county agencies.
   County officials had long planned to replace radio and
computerized dispatch consoles at a cost of about $1 million.
   Existing electronics were pulled out at three of the center's
seven dispatching stations Tuesday and telephone company workers
had scarcely connected phone lines to the new equipment when the
quake hit at 5:04 p.m., England said.
   If the earthquake had struck 10 minutes earlier, England said,
the calls would have gone to the four dispatchers operating
existing equipment, overloading the system.
   ``The minute the power came back on (from emergency generators),
every phone line on the all the consoles was lit,'' England said.
   Most of the calls concerned structure damage or fires.
   England said each operator handled about 10 calls a minute in
the frantic hours after the quake. The center remained staffed 24
hours a day with additional dispatchers loaned by San Mateo county.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
