<DOCNO> AP891021-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 0050EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-RescueStress     10-21 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Rescue Stress,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Round-the-Clock Grief Counseling Accompanies Rescue Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As workers continue the painstaking
effort to chip away freeway concrete from crushed motorists,
psychologists and counselors have launched their own
round-the-clock effort to help rescuers cope.
   Denver psychologist Tom Williams said Friday the slowness of the
recovry effort and the extent of the carnage are particularly
frustrating for workers, who may be susceptible to long-term
emotional problems.
   ``The biggie is when they go back to their regular jobs, they
feel so meaningless,'' said Williams, who was coordinating the
on-site counseling program.
   Stress from the rescue is building up, said Williams, who urged
workers to share their concerns and problems with friends as well
as professional counselors.
   ``If you don't deal with it, it's going to come up and bite you
on the butt later,'' Williams said. ``They might not want to be
rescue workers later.''
   As days pass and workers continue pounding through pavement in
their search for bodies, workers struggle with the frustrations of
slow equipment, he said.
   Typically, rescuers are accustomed to retrieving people who can
be saved, but the chances of discovering a survivor are now
extremely slim, he said.
   ``With every passing hour, the little candle in the tunnel ...
dims for them,'' Williams said. ``It's amazing, the strength of
character these people have.''
   The rescue scene is overwhelming, said the former career Marine
who served two tours of duty in Vietnam.
   ``It just reminds me of being in Vietnam for a couple of
years,'' said Williams. ``It smelled like sort of the same thing.''
</TEXT>
