<DOCNO> AP891021-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 0028EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SFQuake-Marina     10-21 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Marina,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marina Residents Dash to Save Personal Belongings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One person grabbed a priceless collection
of jazz records. Others searched for photo albums. Some piled up
chairs, chests and everything else they could on the streets.
   ``Our poor little lives are right here on the sidewalk,'' said
Patrice Gehrke, 36, packing items from furniture to ferns in the
back of a pickup truck Friday.
   For residents of the city's upscale Marina District whose homes
may have to be demolished, Friday was a dash to salvage whatever
they could from the rubble of Tuesday's earthquake.
   They stuffed their belongings into Mercedes, BMWs and other
luxury cars if they couldn't find rental trucks or pickups. Others
carried away goods in shopping carts, toy wagons, cardboard boxes,
laundry baskets and garbage bags.
   Residents were supposed to have just 15 minutes to grab all
their valuables. Those whose buildings will be torn down were given
red tags and escorted into their homes by a corps of officials
wearing orange vests and hard hats.
   But the time limit was largely ignored. Some tossed possessions
through upper-floor windows.
   ``I felt like I just won a free hour in the supermarket on one
of those TV game shows,'' said Al Challacomb, guarding his stash of
belongings on a buckled sidewalk.
   The mood was not always lighthearted.
   Some people returned to find their homes and apartments
collapsed. One couple stood in the street in a tearful embrace.
   Jennifer Ritz tried not to cry as she squeezed clothes, artwork,
chairs, tables and knickknacks into every available inch of her
friend's blue Mercedes.
   ``You feel rushed, and you can't stop to think of what you
should take,'' said Ms. Ritz, a legal secretary.
   ``I'm alive, but I've lost certain aspects of my life,'' she
said, sobbing. ``I don't know where I'm going. I don't know what
I'm doing. It's terribly unsettling. I just feel like I'm lost.''
   Ways of life crumbled along with stucco condominiums and posh
apartments in the neighborhood, the worst-hit in San Francisco
because its homes were built on landfill, not bedrock.
   As many as 60 homes either collapsed or will be torn down. Many
others were too severely damaged to live in. Damage was so bad
police cordoned off eight square blocks after gas leaks were
detected.
   When residents were allowed back in, the operation looked like a
grotesque sidewalk sale. Streets held motley piles of leather
couches, cedar chests, mahogany trunks, lamps, paintings, chairs,
televisions, stereos, VCRs, skis, snowshoes, vacuum cleaners,
microwaves and mattresses.
   Janet Wyleczuk, 28, was able to grab her dishes, clothes and
personal mementoes out of an apartment scheduled to be demolished.
   ``This was our last chance,'' she said. ``I was able to get a
piece of my past before starting n.''
   ``All I cared about was my photo albums,'' said Lisa Radomski.
   Helmeted motorcycle police officers and Red Cross volunteers
assisted with the chores, huffing and puffing their way down the
stairs.
   Diane Whitacre, 47, hoisted a drawing board on her shoulder so
she could get on with her free-lance work.
   ``The most important thing to me was the stuff I need to make a
living. Life does go on,'' said Ms. Whitacre.
   ``You can always buy another bed. You can always buy new
clothes.''

</TEXT>
