<DOCNO> AP891021-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 0052EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Souvenirs     10-21 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Souvenirs,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>They're Here: Quake T-Shirts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was as inevitable as The Big One
promises to be.
   Earthquake T-shirts, with such slogans as ``I Survived the Great
Quake 1989,'' began popping up in tourist corners of San Francisco
just days after the quake.
   ``Everybody wants one thing,'' Moishe Sewell said at a
Fisherman's Wharf shirt shop Friday. ``They don't care how much it
costs. They say, `When can I have one?'''
   T-shirts from the disastrous quake that rumbled through Northern
California have surpassed World Series shirts in popularity in this
baseball-crazy city.
   ``America leads the way in cashing in at times like this,'' said
Lisa Cozens, a tourist from Melbourne, Australia. ``People may
still be trapped in the rubble, but the T-shirts are here.''
   She bought a shirt.
   Other shirts available included: ``6.9 _ '89 _ Bay Area Quake,''
for $10, and ``I Survived the Quake _ 7.0,'' for $20.
   Quake-related T-shirts were, on average, about twice as
expensive as other tourist shirts, such as ``Alcatraz Swim Team.''
   The owner of one of nine T-shirt stores on Jefferson Street at
Fisherman's Wharf said he sold 1,000 shirts in 30 minutes one
morning.
   Sewell was selling quake shirts for $20 apiece, and he
characterized the sales as a public service.
   ``The only way to help the city at a time like this is to fill
its coffers,'' said Sewell. ``If we didn't fill our coffers,
someone else would fill theirs.''
   Some shirt merchants said they would donate proceeds to relief
efforts. Shop owner Nick Hoppe said he would kick in $8 for each
$16 shirt he sold.
   One shop owner, Bertha Jimenez, said she would not sell any
earthquake T-shirts.
   ``People were killed,'' she said. ``I feel terrible. I am not
going to sell a shirt like that. It would make me feel too sad. Not
right now, anyway.
   ``Maybe next week. Come back next week. I'll probably have some
then.''
</TEXT>
