<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 0053EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-PilotSuspended     10-21 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pilot Suspended,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot of Wandering Plane Loses Right To Fly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration won't
allow Thomas Root, who ended up in the Atlantic Ocean after flying
unconscious for several hours last July, to pilot planes again
anytime soon.
   The communications lawyer said Friday the FAA had pulled the
medical certificate he needs to fly, but that he wouldn't take a
plane in the air anyway.
   ``It would be a very foolhardy thing for me to do to go flying
without knowing what caused the blackout,'' Root said after
receiving a letter informing him of the FAA decision.
   Root, whose Washington communications law firm filed for
bankruptcy after the July 13 incident, said he would turn in his
certificate as ordered.
   But Root added, ``I don't need the FAA to tell me it would be
dumb to fly.''
   The FAA said Root was suspended because he refused to supply all
relevant medical documents, including psychiatric records from his
treatment in Hollywood, Fla., after the flight.
   Root suffered from a gunshot wound he said must have occurred
when a pistol he kept in the cockpit discharged, apparently as the
plane hit the water off Bermuda.
   Root said he no longer owns a plane and had not flown since the
incident that occurred as he was on a business flight from
Washington to Rocky Mount, N.C. Root's pilot's certificate was not
suspended, but he cannot fly without medical certification.
   In a letter dated Wednesday, FAA counsel Donald P. Byrne told
Root FAA Administrator James B. Busey ordered the suspension and
``safety in air transportation or air commerce requires the
immediate effectiveness of this order.''
   The letter said Root had 10 days to appeal to the National
Transportation Safety Board, which is investigating the incident.
   Root has challenged in court the board's use of his psychiatric
records, claiming Florida law protects their confidentiality.
   Root's attorney, Gene Propper, said the hospital had refused to
release the records but inadvertently sent them to the safety board
along with other medical documents.
</TEXT>
