<FIRST>r w PM-US-Panama     10-21 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Panama,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Sanctions to Penalize Americans Who Do Business with Noriega</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is expected to
announce next week that it will make it a crime for any American to
do business with Panama's Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega or firms in
which he has an interest.
   The penalty for violators is a jail term or fines of $500,000,
officials said Friday.
   The sanction is the product of an effort by the administration
to find ways of pressuring Noriega without further damaging the
Panamanian economy. In an additional bid to deprive Panama of
sorely needed income, the administration also is considering
barring Panamanian-flag vessels from U.S. ports, said the
administration officials.
   Panama has been in a steep economic decline over the past year
and a half, partly as a result of limited sanctions imposed by the
United States.
   Many of the more than 30 firms targeted by the new sanctions are
used as intermediaries for illegal trade between the United States
and Cuba.
   The U.S. move will not only tighten the embargo against Cuba but
will also affect firms in which Noriega has an interest, said the
officials, who asked not to be identified.
   The sanction was first reported by The Los Angeles Times in its
Friday editions. State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler had
no comment on the report.
   Cuba has found the Panamanian firms identified with Noriega to
be useful, using them to import high technology U.S.-made items
which would otherwise be beyond Cuba's reach because of the trade
embargo.
   The firms also have served as conduits for illegal Cuban exports
to the United States, officials said, speaking on condition they
not be identified.
   The Bush administration has been searching for additional ways
to weaken Noriega since long before the abortive coup attempt
against him almost three weeks ago.
   The administration has not ruled out the use of force but
visiting Spanish Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez said Friday any
such step would be unwise.
   ``Interventionism is never desirable,'' Gonzalez said shortly
before ending his two-day visit here.
   He praised President Bush for not committing U.S. forces to
all-out support for the rebel officers who revolted against Noriega.
   Gonzalez has called for new elections in Panama and for the
newly elected leadership to have the authority to name a new
Defense Force commander to replace Noriega.
</TEXT>
