<FIRST>r w PM-ComputerMonitoring     10-21 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Computer Monitoring,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Leader Speaks About Abuses From Computer Monitoring</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: 9to5 in 2nd graf is correct</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a clerical workers' union says
employers are using computer surveillance to supervise their
employees out of ``control and fear.''
   Karen Nussbaum, executive director of 9to5, the National
Association of Working Women, appealed to computer specialists
Friday to help curb abuses that she says are leaving many of the
nation's lowest-paid workers frustrated in their workplace.
   ``A management strategy characterized by this lack of commitment
to and faith in the workforce requires a supervision style based on
control and fear,'' she said. ``Surveillance and control now take
the place of supervision, commitment and training.''
   ``You are the creators of this wonderful technology,'' she told
a meeting sponsored by Computer Professionals for Social
Responsibility, a public interest group based in Palo Alto, Calif.
``But it is misused. And there is no one with more credibility than
you to speak out against this misuse.''
   Ms. Nussbaum also serves as president of District 925 of the
Service Employees International Union, representing about 10,000
clerical workers.
   Computer monitoring is most widely used with workers using video
display terminals. Modern technology enables employers to
automatically monitor a variety of work performance data, including
keyboard strokes, typing mistakes, time spent on each phone call
and rest breaks.
   The congressional Office of Technology Assessment has said
``there are strong arguments that the present extent of
computer-based monitoring is only a preview of growing
technological capabilities for monitoring, surveillance and worker
testing on the job.''
   ``If this is the case, then there may be a need for a new
balance between workers' rights to privacy or autonomy in the
workplace and management requirements for information,'' OTA said
in a 1987 report.
   Several states _ including Connecticut, Massachusetts,
Minnesota, New Jersey, Oregon and Rhode Island _ are considering
bills that seek to regulate computer monitoring practices.
   Industry management officials generally argue that computer
monitoring, if properly used, benefits employees by providing an
objective basis for evaluating work performance and rewarding more
productive workers.
   Ms. Nussbaum cited a survey released earlier this year by the
Massachusetts Coalition on New Office Technology, a Boston-based
union-affiliated group, which took questionnaire responses from
more than 700 electronically monitored office workers.
   The survey found 62 percent of the respondents were not informed
they would be monitored prior to hiring, 75 percent of the workers
said monitoring lowers morale and 80 percent said monitoring makes
their job more stressful.
   ``This survey shows deep alienation from the (work) process. And
these feelings are substantiated by study after study,'' Ms.
Nussbaum said.
</TEXT>
