<SECOND>PM-BRF--Textbook Flap,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Historians Protest Japanese Decision Not To Revise Textbooks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty Chinese scholars expressed ``surprise and
indignation'' over a Tokyo court ruling against revising textbooks
that avoid calling Japan's 1930s attack on China an aggression.
   ``We Chinese are reluctant to keep bringing up the bitter past,
but that does not mean that we can allow the Japanese to hurt
Chinese feelings by distorting history,'' the academics said in a
statement Friday later carried by the official Xinhua News Agency.
   China says at least 200,000 people were killed when Japanese
troops invaded Nanjing in 1937, and it has strongly objected to
Japanese textbooks characterizing the military campaign as an
``advance'' rather than aggression.
   The scholars, attending a symposium on the Sino-Japanese War of
1937-45, said Japanese aggression against China during that period
was firmly maintained by the international community.
   Tokyo District Court this month ruled the government's
inspection of textbooks is legal but said there were mistakes in
the Education Ministry's orders that parts of a historian's
textbook be rewritten.
