<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--TowerofPisa     10-21 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Tower of Pisa,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Official Vows To Keep Leaning Tower Open Until Forced To Close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PISA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city official said the leaning tower will
stay open to tourists despite a scientific committee's conclusion
that Pisa's most famous monument is dangerous.
   The committee appointed by the Public Works Ministry said the
180-foot tower, which has been leaning for 800 years, tilts more
each year, that some of the stone work is crumbling and pieces of
stone have fallen off.
   They said officials should consider immediately closing the
tower, which now leans about 13 feet off the perpendicular.
   ``I will keep the tower open until I am forced to close it,''
Giuseppe Toniolo, chairman of a city committee responsible for
preservation of the tower, said Friday.
   Mayor Giacomino Granchi said he hoped the committee's
recommendations would be quickly evaluated by the Public Works
Ministry. He said closing the tower would cause economic problems
for the city but added: ``it is my wish that the problem with the
tower is confronted decisively, seriously and openly.''
