<FIRST>r a PM-Hastings     10-21 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hastings,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Removed by Senate Will Run For Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rejected by judicial colleagues and removed from
the bench by Congress, Alcee L. Hastings will take his case to
Florida voters.
   Within minutes of the announcement Friday of his impeachment
conviction in the Senate, the 53-year-old veteran civil rights
activist said he would seek the Democratic nomination for the 1990
governor's race.
   ``Not only can I be elected, I think I will,'' Hastings said in
Washington. ``Floridians are tired of ordinariness, and if there's
nothing else I bring to an experience, it is not ordinariness.
   Hastings is the sixth federal judge removed and the first
impeached after acquittal by a jury.
   ``I'm not disgraced. The Constitution is disgraced,'' Hastings
said. ``Life goes on, and there will be joy in the morning.''
   He held a party for friends in Washington late Friday,
declaring, ``We was robbed.''
   Hastings' last foray into politics was a lopsided defeat in the
1970 U.S. Senate Democratic primary in Florida.
   Jon Peck, a spokesman for Republican Gov. Bob Martinez,
belittled the former judge's chances in the political arena.
   ``Based on that track record, he's going to run for governor?''
Peck asked. ``Anybody who wants to is welcome to run for governor.
They'll have to take on an incumbent who is going to get
re-elected.''
   The governor, who was on a glass-bottom boat in the Florida Keys
with Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan, laughed when told of
Hastings' announcement for governor.
   ``You'll have to ask George Stuart and Bill Nelson about that,''
he said, referring to the Democrats in the race.
   Said state Democratic Party Chairman Simon Ferro: ``I would
certainly like to sit down with him to assess his opportunities and
his chances and how they might affect the race. That's about as
much as I can tell you at this point.''
   Hastings, appointed in 1979 by President Carter as the first
black U.S. district judge in Florida after a career of civil rights
litigation and experience as a state judge, plans to return to law
practice while gearing up a gubernatorial campaign.
   Plagued by clogged arteries, he also has indicated he wants to
undergo surgery before his federal insurance expires in 30 days.
   Under a cloud since an FBI sting operation probing alleged
case-fixing began in 1981, Hastings has refused to step aside
despite mounting evidence and accusations against him. He and his
attorneys have argued that charges against him were racially tinged
witchhunts.
   He was convicted Friday on eight of 17 impeachment counts. The
Senate voted 95-0 to acquit on charges he leaked confidential
wiretap information to Metro-Dade County Mayor Steve Clark.
   Black reaction Friday was indignant.
   ``It's a definite travesty to our justice system,'' said
Roosevelt Walters, head of the Fort Lauderdale branch of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People. ``We
have to wonder who is next? Who will be singled out?''
   The judge was voted out for allegedly conspiring to take a
$150,000 payoff to fix a court case. A federal jury in Miami
acquitted him in 1983, although his friend William A. Borders, a
Washington attorney, was convicted of bribery conspiracy in a
separate trial.
   Judicial colleagues launched an investigation that led to
Hastings' impeachment last year in the House, which accused him of
plotting to obtain a bribe, lying during his trial and an unrelated
charge of improperly disclosing federal wiretap information.
</TEXT>
