<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Bush Bjt   10-21 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Bush, Bjt,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0435 to change category code.</HEAD>
<HEAD>President Vows Quick Federal Help to Quake-Ravaged Bay Area</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, astonished at the
destruction the Northern California earthquake tore through the San
Francisco Bay area, is pledging the government will ``do what's
necessary to fix it.''
   ``There's no ceiling on the compassion of the American people,''
Bush said Friday after what he called ``a very moving day'' touring
sites of devastation the earthquake left behind, including the
collapsed freeway that entombed uncounted bodies.
   ``I'm willing to do what's needed to be done,'' Bush said as he
walked amid the rubble of Santa Cruz's shattered business mall, a
few miles from the Tuesday quake's epicenter.
   He didn't promise a specific amount, and declined several times
to rule out the possibility of tax increases to pay for recovery
costs.
   State officials estimate the total damage at $5.5 billion, but
some estimates say damage may reach $10 billion,
   ``In terms of what it will cost, I don't know,'' said Bush, who
has already signed a disaster relief declaration for seven Bay-area
counties and authorized an initial $273 million. He said Washington
will work with local and state governments ``to see the suffering
is alleviated, the restoration begins.''
   Bush, who won office on a firm pledge of no new taxes, said,
``I'm going to do what is necessary to have the federal government
fulfill its obligation,'' and repeated substantially the same
phrase when asked if that meant new taxes.
   California Gov. George Deukmejian has said he is willing to face
a state tax increase, if necessary.
   Bush appeared shocked at the destruction he saw as he walked
along the collapsed Interstate 880 in Oakland and flew by
helicopter over the eerily quiet Oakland-San Francisco Bay Bridge.
A 50-foot gap in the upper level of the eight-mile, two-deck bridge
gaped where the earthquake knocked a slab of roadway loose.
   At the Oakland highway leading to the bridge, Bush exclaimed
``Jesus'' on seeing the flattened concrete and twisted beams where
workers are still searching for victims. He walked alongside and
even under the highway where flattened cars were crushed beneath
the top portion of the freeway.
   ``I am deeply moved by this, saddened in some ways, yet very
stimulated by this team effort,'' the president said.
   Pressed on whether he would waive tight budget restraints to
speed aid to the region, Bush said, ``We're going to do what is
necessary to fix it ... We will do what is necessary to fulfill our
federal responsibility.''
   At each stop, he greeted rescue workers and praised the
volunteer efforts of those who are helping put the area back
together.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner, newly designated to
head federal quake-recovery efforts, said the administration was
putting together a relief package for California, but gave no
figures.
   Bush spent five hours in Northern California for a firsthand
look at some spots worst hit by Tuesday's 6.9-magnitude earthquake.
   He later said his most emotional moment was when he talked to a
surgeon who had to amputate the leg of a 6-year-old boy to rescue
him from a smashed car on I-880. Bush then telephoned the boy's
father.
   ``I had a chance to tell him that the American people are
rooting for him,'' Bush told reporters.
   Bush also taped a public service television announcement
offering encouragement to Bay area residents and urging Americans
around the nation to contribute to volunteer organizations.
   Rep. Norman Mineta, a Democrat from nearby San Jose, said the
damages could run as high as $8 billion to $10 billion. He said the
$2.5 billion suggested Thursday by House Speaker Thomas S. Foley
``is not enough.''
   Democratic Rep. Leon Panetta, whose district includes Santa
Cruz, said his area would need ``in excess of $1 billion.''
   San Francisco Mayor Art Agnos gave a damage estimate of $2
billion and said up to 2,000 San Franciscans had been made homeless.
   Oakland Mayor Lionel Wilson said his area suffered about $1.3
billion in damage to buildings.
</TEXT>
