<FIRST>r i PM-China-Quake     10-21 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Quake,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says 27,500 Homes Destroyed, 50,000 Homeless</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flurry of earthquakes that hit northern China
this week destroyed 27,500 homes and left more than 50,000
homeless, Radio Beijing said today.
   The broadcast, monitored in Tokyo, also said there have been
1,500 aftershocks, four between 5.0 and 6.0 on the Richter scale,
since the initial temblors devastated farming villages late
Wednesday and early Thursday.
   There were no new reports of casualties today in the official
press, which has carried little coverage of the quakes. Official
reports Friday said 29 people were killed and more than 150 injured.
   The Communist Party's People's Daily said today that the temblor
caused damage in 40 villages over a 320-square-mile area, mostly in
northern Shanxi province.
   It said 1,600 soldiers were mobilized to help relief operations
and that such items as bread, noodles, chopsticks, quilts, tents,
mats and medical supplies were rushed to the affected areas.
   However, the report emphasized that production and commerce were
little affected by the quakes. It said coal production in Datong,
the province's main city, exceeded its normal daily output Thursday.
   The Beijing Radio report also said 32,400 houses were damaged
and in danger of collapse, and that cracks had appeared in the
Shanxi No. 2 dam.
   A Western reporter in the stricken area Friday night said
peasants rigged tents of quilts and straw and gathered around fires
in near-freezing temperatures.
   Northern Shanxi is an impoverished area located on a windswept
plain about 4,000 feet above sea level. The local population works
in coal mines or scratches out a living by growing wheat and corn
in the dusty, infertile soil.
   Many live in homes of mud and stone that easily crumble in
earthquakes.
   Chinese seismologists said the quakes were the worst to hit
northern China since 1976, when a temblor measuring at least 7.8 on
the Richter scale killed 240,000 people in northeastern Tangshan.
   The strongest quake Thursday registered 6.1 on the Richter scale.
   Despite the destruction, casualties appeared to be low because
many people fled their homes after a first quake late Wednesday and
were outside when the second big tremor destroyed their dwellings.
   The Richter scale gauges the energy released by an earthquake,
as measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph. A quake
measuring 6.0 can cause severe damage in a populated area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891021-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 0152EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CollegeRacism 1stLd-Writethru a0427 10-21 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-College Racism, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0427,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>New England Universities Grappling With Racism</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Brown University explanation
of handling of event, RECASTING to show that event rescheduled sted canceled,
subs out extraneous material, picks up 8th graf pvs, `There have...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two New England universities are using different tactics to
grapple with racist attacks and racial hostility on their campuses.
   The University of Massachusetts launched a week of events aimed
at greater racial understanding. At Brown University, authorities
reacting to attacks on Asian and white students said they were
canceling a dance sponsored by a black fraternity, but later the
dance was rescheduled.
   Some students had protested the cancellation.
   ``The whole black community is upset. We feel the university is
holding blacks liable for the attacks in Providence,'' said John
Robertson, vice president of Omega Psi Phi fraternity. ``They're
cutting the social lives of black students at Brown right out from
underneath them. They're taking away the places we go to get away
from the academic rigors at Brown.''
   Robert Reichley, vice president for university affairs, said the
event had been rescheduled and moved to a ``more internally located
part of campus.''
   Officials at the Ivy League school in Providence, R.I., said the
party was moved to discourage high school or non-Brown students
from attending.
   There have been 19 attacks on 22 Brown students since classes
began in September. At least 14 white and Asian men described their
attackers as black teen-agers, believed to be from off-campus.
   Meanwhile, at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst,
officials opened Civility Week, an eight-day series of events
designed to promote racial harmony on the campus. The series of
events, being held for the second year, marks a brawl that followed
the 1986 World Series. It left one black student seriously injured.
   A number of racial incidents have occurred at New England
campuses in the last two years.
   At exclusive Smith College, racist notes were slipped under the
doors of minority students last spring. At Hampshire and Williams
colleges, also located in western Massachusetts, sit-ins were held
in the spring of 1988 to demand more attention to racial issues on
campus.
   In March of this year ``go home'' notes were shoved under a
black student's door at UMass. This semester, a black man was
assaulted by three white non-students.
   Racism on campus is difficult to predict and hard to stamp out,
said the director of the National Institute Against Prejudice and
Violence.
   ``We're talking about a form of terrorism and there isn't any
defense,'' said Howard Ehrlich, director of research at the
Baltimore-based institute. ``In order to build up a defense you
wind up sacrificing a lot of people's personal rights and
liberties.''
   Ehrlich said the institute estimates one out of five minority
students are victimized during the course of an academic year,
based on case studies on a dozen campuses.
   He said he recommends that colleges take a two-pronged approach
to racism: institute stiff punishment for offenders and establish a
core of educational programs.
   ``You cannot organize to stop random acts, so what you try to do
in a sense is to inoculate a campus to deal with the effects and
the impacts,'' he said. ``You can watch your curriculum and you can
watch the way in which the university as an institution deals with
matters of group relations.''
</TEXT>
