<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     10-21 0746</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>NJ Reps Want Express Trains to Include Stop in State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some New Jersey members of Congress don't want
their state to be sacrificed in the competition between Amtrak and
the Trump Shuttle for the New York-Washington travel market.
   The national railroad company is preparing to offer three
additional express metroliners between New York and Washington at
month's end to retain its dominance of the air-rail route.
   But the New Jersey representatives, led by Republican Rep.
Matthew Rinaldo, say Newark is being unfairly left out of the
quicker metroliner service.
   ``This decision by your office is a shortsighted effort that
disserves the Newark-New York metropolitan area,'' Rinaldo said in
a letter to W. Graham Claytor Jr.
   Garden State riders account for 1.2 million Amtrak passengers
each year, half of whom board or disembark at Newark.
   Amtrak spokesman Cliff Black said New Jersey service is not
being sacrificed for the express trains.
   ``We are not reducing the number of metroliner service trains in
New Jersey that are stopping in New Jersey,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Lamia Sausage Voluntarily Recalling Meat Products</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says Lamia's
Sausage Co. of St. Louis, Mo., is voluntarily recalling all of its
meat products because they may contain high levels of sulfites.
   The company sells some products across the counter in its St.
Louis retail store, but most products are distributed to
restaurants in nearby areas in Missouri and Illinois.
   Lester M. Crawford, administrator of the department's Food
Safety and Inspection Service, said Friday that no illnesses have
been reported but that consumers and other purchasers should
``immediately return any products produced by the company.''
   The recalled products include: Lamia's Spedini's, bratwurst,
Italian sausage with cheese, Italian sausage with beef and tomato
sauce, Italian sausage (pork), ground beef patties, ground beef,
and Italia Brand Beef Patty Mix. Products can be identified further
by the establishment code ``Est. 13000'' inside the USDA inspection
seal.
   Crawford said that because of the high levels of sulfites found
during testing, sulfite-sensitive consumers could become seriously
ill or even die.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Bush Working With South Americans for Drug Summit</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is working with
officials from three South American cocaine-producing countries to
determine a site for a drug summit, a White House official says.
   ``We can't rule anything in or out,'' deputy press secretary
Alixe Glen said Friday.
   She commented in response to questions about a story in the
Washington Times, which said the Secret Service had informally
rejected Cartagena, Colombia, as the site for the summit because
the president's safety could not be guaranteed in a country torn by
drug-related violence.
   The newspaper said Puerto Rico was the most likely site, and
indeed, officials have mentioned that it is a leading contender.
   Ms. Glen said the United States was working with Peru, Colombia
and Bolivia to determine the location, timing, agenda and
participants for the summit. She said representatives of the four
countries will meet Nov. 20 to decide the details.
   Secret Service spokesman Robert Snow declined to comment on the
report.

</TEXT>
<NOTE>Soviets Buy More US Grain</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says private
exporting companies have sold the Soviet Union an additional 2.82
million metric tons of U.S. corn, a record for a single purchase,
for delivery in 1989-90 under a long-term supply agreement.
   The department said Friday that 105,000 tons of soybean meal
also were sold to the Soviet Union for 1989-90 delivery.
   Orders since Oct. 1, the beginning of the agreement's new year,
now total nearly 7.87 million tons of corn, 143,700 tons of
soybeans and 430,000 tons of soybean meal.
   Two of the orders since Oct. 1 have been record breakers,
according to a list compiled by the department's Foreign
Agricultural Service for sales going back more than 10 years. The
latest for 2.82 million tons topped the previous high of 2 million
tons reported on Oct. 3.
   U.S. grain sales to Moscow in 1988-89 totalled a record of more
than 21.7 million tons, including more than 16.3 million tons of
corn and nearly 5.4 million tons of wheat.
   In addition, 1988-89 sales included 442,500 tons of soybeans,
1.35 million tons of soybean meal and 1.02 million tons of grain
sorghums.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 2.82 million tons
of corn would be more than 111 million bushels.
</TEXT>
