<FIRST>r a PM-NationalGeographic     10-21 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-National Geographic,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Society to End Relationship with Station that Co-Produced Specials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 15 years and 27 Emmys, the National
Geographic Society will sever its relationship with WQED-TV, the
station that has co-produced the National Geographic specials.
   The society has announced it will take over management and
production of the specials in 1992, when the current contract
expires.
   WETA-TV in Washington, D.C., will replace WQED as the station
that will make the program available to public television stations
across the nation. WETA will not be involved in production of the
specials other than as a consultant.
   ``Almost everything we do at the society is done in-house,'' Tim
Kelly, vice president and director of television at National
Geographic, said Thursday. ``It just seemed like the time in our
evolution to let things play out in our outside relationship and
bring the specials back in-house.''
   Chevron Corp., based in San Francisco, continue as sponsor.
   WQED and the society have co-produced the award-winning specials
since they moved to public television in 1974. The society
terminated its contract with WQED in February, and the parties have
been negotiating since then.
   WQED Communications Vice President Tom Skinner, executive
producer of the specials, issued the following statement from
London, where he and other top WQED executives are attending a
festival:
   ``The combined efforts of the many talented WQED people who have
contributed to the success of the specials will now be available to
work on our upcoming eight-hour `Space Age' series and our
continuing `Infinite Voyage' specials, among our other efforts soon
to be launched,'' he said.
   ``Space Age,'' a $6 million co-production with the National
Academy of Sciences, is timed to coincide with the 1992
International Space Year.
</TEXT>
