<HEAD>Court Reporter Forced to Complete Murder Trial Transcript In Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAXAHACHIE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court reporter has been jailed more
than two weeks for failing to finish the transcript of a 1987
double murder trial that is now under appeal.
   Donna Creel of Red Oak was jailed Oct. 4 after the Texas Court
of Criminal Appeals issued a contempt order. She remained in the
Ellis County Jail Friday, officials said.
   Mrs. Creel took nearly 8,000 pages of notes from the murder
trial of Kenneth Dewayne Thomas, who was convicted for the March
1986 murder of a Dallas attorney and his wife. No action can be
taken on the appeal until the appeals court obtains a transcript.
   The transcript of the trial was originally due in November 1987
and Ms. Creel was given four extensions, the last until Aug. 7,
before the nine-member appeals court issued the contempt order.
   Mrs. Creel's attorney, Ron Bunch, said she is spending up to 20
hours a day working on the transcript and expects to finish next
week.
   ``She's going to be all right,'' Bunch said. ``She's not getting
much sleep.''
</TEXT>
