<SECOND>PM-Korea-Panama,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panamanian Military Attache Said To Seek Asylum in U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Panamanian Embassy official said
today that a Panamanian military attache appeared to have sought
political asylum in the United States after being implicated in a
recent coup attempt.
   The embassy official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
retired Maj. Leonidas Pretelt, 44, secretly left the South Korean
capital Thursday with his wife and three children on a flight to
Oregon.
   ``We are sure that he left Seoul to seek asylum in the United
States,'' the official said. ``He was suspected of being involved
in a coup attempt and forced to retire from active duty,'' he said
without elaborating.
   There was no immediate comment from U.S. officials.
   A group of Panamanian military officers tried Oct. 3 to topple
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, indicted in Florida on drug
trafficking charges and whose refusal to step down has prompted
Washington to impose sanctions against the Panamanian government.
   The South Korean national police, at the request of the
Panamanian Embassy, discovered Friday that Pretelt secretly left
Seoul for Portland, Ore., aboard a Delta Air Lines plane Thursday.
