<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-Texas     10-21 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Texas,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Refuses to Put Abortion on Agenda of Special Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bill Clements stunned abortion foes by
refusing to put the issue on the agendas of two scheduled special
sessions of the state Legislature.
   Abortion opponents angered by Clements' decision Friday recalled
the governor's previous statement that Texans ``can bet on'' a
special abortion session to react to the latest U.S. Supreme Court
abortion ruling.
   ``I'm glad I didn't put any money on it,'' said Bill Price,
president of Texans United for Life.
   Clements Friday said abortion wouldn't be on the agenda of
either the November special session called to consider workers'
compensation or the spring session on school financing. But his
press secretary, Rossanna Salazar, said, ``Whether it (abortion) is
the subject of a future special session, anything is possible.''
   Particularly galling to anti-abortion activists is the fact the
governor, a Republican, is opposed to abortion.
   ``I consider it to be a betrayal,'' Price said of Clements'
statement. ``He's playing political football with the lives of
unborn children.''
   A Supreme Court ruling in July gave states wider powers to limit
abortions.
   Clements, who isn't seeking re-election, will be out of office
by the time the next regular session begins in January 1991. The
governor calls and sets the agenda for special legislative sessions.
   Ms. Salazar said Clements hasn't changed his anti-abortion
beliefs. The governor is against abortions except in the cases of
rape, incest, or if the life of the mother is in danger, she said.
   ``We're not going to cloud the issue of the special session on
workers' compensation by putting in these other extraneous
issues,'' Clements said of the first special session.
   Ms. Salazar said Clements wouldn't put abortion on the agenda of
the second session, either. ``The governor believes that this issue
would be better served if it were considered during a regular
session,'' she said.
   She said Clements believes Texas lawmakers need to wait for
additional abortion cases pending before the U.S. Supreme Court.
   Current Texas law forbids abortions in the third trimester,
unless the life of the mother is in danger.
</TEXT>
