<FIRST>r a PM-RussianSailor     10-21 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Russian Sailor,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sailor Rescued after Drifting for 67 Days in Pacific</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Russian sailor trying to cross the Pacific in
a 20-foot sailboat was rescued by a passing container ship after
drifting for 67 days, the Coast Guard reported.
   The 30-year-old man appeared to be in satisfactory condition,
although he had lost a lot of weight, a Coast Guard official said
Friday.
   No one on the container ship speaks Russian, and the sailor
doesn't speak English, so his story was pieced together through
sign language and by looking at his log book, said the coast guard
official, who refused to be quoted by name.
   It wasn't clear if the man was trying to defect, the Coast Guard
official said.
   Coast Guard investigators believe the 20-foot vessel left the
Soviet port of Vladivostok about June 2, bound for San Francisco,
and lost its mast August 14, the official said.
   It drifted until Friday, when the sailor was picked up by the
U.S. container ship President Roosevelt about 1,850 miles northwest
of Honolulu.
   The container ship was headed for Guam and should arrive there
with the survivor Sunday night.
</TEXT>
