<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-KGB     10-21 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-KGB,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>KGB to Reduce Restricted Border Zone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union will cut its restricted border
zones by 90 percent and take down the barbed wire in many areas,
KGB officials told a Soviet legislative committee.
   Tass, the Soviet news agency, said the committee was told
border-crossing procedures will also be simplified. The committee
oversees the KGB and the Defense Ministry.
   In its report Friday, Tass did not specify the area now
protected by 200,000 border guards or how the zone will be cut.
   The KGB is trying to soften its image and move away from a Cold
War mentality, in keeping with President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
push for greater openness and democracy.
   A KGB official said Moscow's better relations with neighbors
prompted the move and KGB head, Vladimir A. Kryuchkov, said there
was no longer any reason to maintain such a large border zone, the
news agency said.
   KGB deputy chief Vadim Matrosov told the Defense and Security
Committee the southern border _ particularly with Afghanistan _
requires extra guards to combat smuggling and armed gangs. But in
general, improving relations with China, Iran and NATO members
Turkey and Norway, has meant reduced border tension.
   In some places the forbidden border zone is hundreds of miles
wide and even along the Soviet Union's border with Warsaw Pact
allies, Moscow has strung barbed wire and placed armed KGB guards
in towers.
   Foreigners are barred from a 16-mile-wide strip along the Soviet
borders with Norway, Finland, Iran, Turkey and Afghanistan.
   The country plans to ``remove the barbed-wire entanglement in
many areas,'' Tass said.
   About 3,400 people illegally crossed into border zones since
last year, Tass said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
