<FIRST>r a PM-ShuttleLanding     10-21 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle Landing,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smaller-Than-Normal Crowd of 100,000 Expected at Atlantis Landing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School, work and the
northern California earthquake may limit the crowd of spectators to
100,000 people when the space shuttle lands here next week, a NASA
spokeswoman said.
   Atlantis is scheduled to touch down at this Mojave Desert base
at 12:38 p.m. PDT Monday.
   But there is some possibility that high winds might force NASA
to bring the shuttle back to Earth about 90 minutes early, or one
or two days later, the agency said Friday.
   A weekday landing should draw about 100,000 spectators to the
public viewing site on the east shore of Rogers Dry Lake, said
Nancy Lovato, spokeswoman for the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration.
   ``Had the landing been on a Saturday or Sunday, I'd expect
double that,'' she said. ``But on a Monday people have to go to
school and go to work.''
   Lovato said the crowd also might be reduced by last Tuesday's
earthquake in the San Francisco Bay area.
   ``I don't think we'll have very many people coming from that
area,'' she said. ``They have things to take care of.''
   Atlantis blasted off from Kennedy Space Center in Florida on
Wednesday, and several hours later deployed the Galileo spacecraft
on a six-year trip to the planet Jupiter.
   The biggest crowd to greet a shuttle numbered 500,000 on July 4,
1982, when then-President Reagan was on hand for Columbia's
landing. About 450,000 people watched Discovery land Oct. 3, 1988 _
a Monday, but the first shuttle landing since the Challenger
disaster, Lovato said.
   The viewing site will be opened to the public 24 hours before
Atlantis lands, and access will be closed one hour before the
landing, Lovato said. Two-lane access roads often are congested, so
spectators are advised to arrive early.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
