<SECOND>PM-Weapons Ban,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Blocks Atlanta Ban on Certain Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge barred the city from enforcing an
ordinance which bans sales of semiautomatic assault weapons.
   Judge Luther Alverson of Superior Court in Fulton County ruled
Friday for the second time that only the General Assembly can
regulate the sale of firearms. In July the judge blocked
enforcement of an almost identical Fulton County ordinance.
   Alverson said he would grant temporary restraining orders
against the City Council, police and Mayor Andrew Young.
   Attorney Martha Glisson, a lawyer for Citizens for Safe
Government, a gun-fanciers' group that challenged the law, argued
that the local laws are so vague and broadly written that even
sporting weapons could be considered illegal by police.
   Assistant City Attorney Joe M. Harris argued that the city
ordinance isn't preempted by state law because, he said, it goes
farther than any state legislation now on the books.
   Both ordinances were aimed at limiting drug dealers' access to
weapons like Uzi semiautomatic pistols, rifles and the AK-47
assault rifle.
</TEXT>
