<FIRST>r a PM-SkinheadLawsuit     10-21 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Skinhead Lawsuit,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family of Slain Man Sue White Supremacy Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of a slain Ethiopian immigrant
has sued a white supremacist group and its leader for allegedly
encouraging the thugs who beat him to death with a baseball bat.
   The federal lawsuit filed Friday names White Aryan Resistance,
or WAR, its leader, Tom Metzger, and Metzger's son, John, head of
the Aryan Youth Movement.
   Two men who have been convicted in the death, Kenneth Mieske,
20, and Kyle Brewster, 19, also were named in the suit.
   Mulugeta Seraw, 27, was killed Nov. 13 outside his apartment.
Two of Seraw's friends were severely beaten.
   The lawsuit alleges the defendants are responsible for wrongful
death, conspiracy to violate civil rights and racial intimidation.
It seeks unspecified damages.
   Mieske was sentenced in the spring to life in prison for murder.
Brewster was sentenced Thursday to 10 to 20 years in prison for
manslaughter. Both men also were convicted on racial intimidation
charges.
   A third man charged in the death, Steven Strasser, is scheduled
for trial later this month. Strasser wasn't named in the civil suit.
   Members of neo-Nazi youth gangs are known as ``skinheads''
because the shaved head is an identifying feature among such youths.
   The suit was filed by the Southern Poverty Law Center and the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith on behalf of Seraw's family.
Seraw's son, Henock Seraw, and his father, Seraw Tikuneh, live in
Ethiopia. The estate is being handled by Seraw's uncle, Engedaw
Berhanu of San Francisco.
   Tom Metzger is one of the better-known white supremacists in the
country. Reached at his Southern California home Friday night, he
dismissed the allegations in the lawsuit as ``nonsense.'' He and
his son, he said, didn't know Brewster or Mieske. Further, he said,
``I don't send people to do violence against people. I never have.''
   The complaint filed in Portland alleges that John and Tom
Metzger, as WAR leaders, sent ``agents'' to Portland in October
1988 to encourage Mieske, Brewster and other members of the
skinhead gang East Side White Pride to incite violence against Jews
and Blacks.
   The Metzger agents, who aren't named in the court papers,
allegedly urged members of the skinhead group to call Tom Metzger's
hot line for encouragement and direction. They also gave group
members racist literature that encouraged them to violence, the
lawsuit alleges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
