<FIRST>r a PM-ArtilleryAccident     10-21 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Artillery Accident,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Charged in Artillery Accident That Killed Three</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nickoles is cq in 3rd graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT SILL, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two artillerymen face up to 15 months
confinement for their part in the Sept. 27 accident that killed
three soldiers and wounded 24 when a howitzer round missed its
target by about half a mile.
   Too much powder behind the 105mm howitzer round caused it to
explode near a formation of about 80 soldiers at a rifle range,
Fort Sill spokeswoman Sheila Samples said Friday. Four of the
injured soldiers remain hospitalized.
   Sgt. Edward C. Tyler, 26, of Washington, D.C., and Spec.
Nickoles W. Holly, 24, of Canton, Ohio, were charged this week in
military court, Ms. Samples said.
   Tyler, a howitzer battery section chief, and Holly, a No. 2
cannoneer, are assigned to C Battery, 2nd Battalion, 2nd Field
Artillery.
   Staff Sgt. William Beil said the men had been removed from the
battery and assigned to other duties until the outcome of their
hearing. He said the soldiers were not in confinement.
   If a general court-martial is convened, the men could face
between three and 15 months of confinement, loss of wages, and bad
conduct discharges, Ms. Samples said.
   Maj. Gen. Raphael J. Hallada, the Fort Sill commander, will
determine whether the men will be charged with dereliction of duty
through negligence, negligent homicide, or both charges, she said.
</TEXT>
