<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     10-21 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Front Freezes Northwest, Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front brought rain and cool temperatures to the Pacific
Northwest today, while unseasonably cold temperatures also cooled
the Southeast.
   In the Midwest, the rain and snow that lingered over much of the
region on Thursday and Friday appeared to be moving away, allowing
a warm front out of the West to reach the area.
   While temperatures are expected to rise to the 70s in part of
Iowa and Illinois by Sunday, temperatures were in the 30s and 40s
in the Midwest early today. Rain fell over Detroit, and snow and
rain fell in eastern Wisconsin.
   A series of cold fronts was expected over the Pacific Northwest
this weekend. The cold fronts were expected to dampen the region
and bring snow over the higher elevations of Washington and Nevada.
   In the South, record low temperatures for the date were broken
in several cities Friday, including Corpus Christi, Texas, 39, and
Miami, 58. Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT dipped to 38 at Little Rock,
Ark., and 41 in New Orleans.
   Snow continued into Friday evening over upper Michigan, eastern
Wisconsin, Indiana, Ohio, northeast Kentucky, West Virginia, and
western Virginia.
   Rain fell from New England across New York state and New Jersey.
Three or more inches of rain drenched portions of Vermont and
eastern New York, causing flooding and threats of flooding.
   Rain also extended from the northern third of California to the
Washington coast, and from eastern Washington into northwest
Montana.
   The high temperature for the nation Friday was 95 degrees at
Borrego Springs, Calif.
   Other reports at 3 a.m. EDT:
