<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--AlaskaUnemployment     10-21 0115</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Alaska Unemployment,0117</SECOND>
<HEAD>End of Spill Cleanup Pushes Unemployment Rate to 7.3 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The end of Exxon's oil-spill cleanup
helped push Alaska's unemployment rate up more than a percentage
point to 7.3 percent in September, the Labor Department reported.
   The rate was up from 5.9 percent in August but low compared to
the 8.7 percent rate in September 1988.
   The loss of about 2,700 cleanup jobs and sharp seasonal job
declines in fish processing and tourism reversed a five-month drop
in the state's unemployment rate that began with the cleanup boom.
   The state's unemployment rate from April to August was the
lowest recorded since at least 1976, the department said.
