<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 0535EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpillDecisions     10-21 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill Decisions,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General Says Spill `Trustees' Are Ignoring State's Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Decisions that will affect how Prince
William Sound is restored are being made by anonymous federal
officials who are ignoring local interests, according to Alaska's
attorney general.
   At issue is the Trustee Council, a high-level government group
charged under federal law with determining the long-term damage
from the Exxon Valdez oil spill, an assessment that eventually will
be used to determine how much Exxon Corp. must pay to restore the
environment.
   The council includes the federal secretaries of Interior,
Agriculture and Commerce, and a state representative, Commissioner
Don Collinsworth of the Alaska Department of Fish and Game.
   A group of federal and state scientists and bureaucrats have
been working together on the assessment and related studies, and
they report to the trustees, Attorney General Douglas Baily said
Friday.
   But ``their decisions have regularly been overturned once they
get back to the policy-making people back in Washington,'' he said.
``They'll be rewritten in Washington by parties unknown.''
   The Exxon Valdez hit a reef March 24 and spilled about 11
million gallons of oil into the Prince William Sound. Exxon's
cleanup operation in the sound ended in September but may continue
in the spring.
   The council staff has held several meetings in Washington
without enough notice to permit state representatives to attend,
Baily said. He said the council has yet to name a chairman, or
``lead trustee,'' and to his knowledge the trustees have never met
together.
   ``We're still under the direction of a headless horseperson and
nobody has final say, so nobody's accountable,'' he said.
   ``There has been an inordinate amount of time spent trying to
figure out where we are and to keep track of what other people are
doing at meetings where we are not invited,'' Baily said.
   Bob Walker, an Interior Department spokesman in Washington, said
the federal trustees have met several times with William Reilly,
director of the Environmental Protection Agency. He said Alaskan
officials declined to participate in the meetings.
   Baily disagreed.
   ``I don't know that there's ever been a meeting of the trustees,
period,'' he said. ``I have never heard that they have ever sat
down in the same room on this topic.''
   Federal and state officials were in disagreement about the
formation of the council, with Alaska demanding that Collinsworth
be named the lead trustee.
   Walker acknowledged the dispute was over power.
   ``The feeling of several of the trustees was that they could not
operate that way, that they would be yielding authority they could
not yield,'' he said.
   Baily said that while the state and federal officials in the
field are working well, their recommendations are being ignored.
For example, the staff recently recommended a three-year budget to
fund its research, but officials in Washington limited it to a year
without consulting the state, Baily said.
   ``Many times a report goes back to Washington and it comes out
in a different form.''
   Another brewing dispute, with ramifications beyond the spill, is
over who owns the tidelands and submerged lands in Prince William
Sound.
   Baily said Alaskan officials believe the tide and submerged
lands belong to the state of Alaska, but the federal government,
through the Forest Service, has insisted since the spill that it
owns those lands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
