<FIRST>r a PM-FaultyPacemakers     10-21 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Faulty Pacemakers,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Former Cordis Officials Innocent of Pacemaker Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four former Cordis Corp. officials accused of
selling defective heart pacemakers from 1983 to 1985 have been
found innocent in federal court.
   The defendants were acquitted Friday after a six-week trial on
conspiracy and related charges in what the government claimed was
the sale of 2,200 defective pacemakers and 6,000 corrosion-prone
batteries.
   Harold Hershenson, 62, a former executive vice president; John
Pagones, 64, former vice president for corporate product assurance;
Stephen Vadas, 48, manager for product administration and Dean
Ciporkin, 42, senior reliability assurance engineer all were
cleared by the 12-member federal jury.
   All four left Cordis, which has since sold off its pacemaker
division.
   The Miami-based company itself previously had pleaded guilty and
paid a $764,000 fine, along with $5 million in civil penalties to
various federal agencies.
   The FDA said the pacemakers could have stopped without warning,
yet no deaths were attributed to failure of the devices implanted
under the skin to regulate the heartbeat.
   Company officials knew of the problems, but sold the pacemakers
anyway, according to the charges.
   Cordis' pacemaker business was sold to the Australian medical
device manufacturer Telectronics. Cordis now concentrates on making
catheters for diagnosing and treating heart problems and gauges for
monitoring pressure on the brain.
   A company statement released after the verdict that Cardis was
``extremely gratified'' by the acquittals.
   ``We fully supported the individuals and have always believed
that no crime had been committed,'' the unsigned statement said.
</TEXT>
