<FIRST>r n PM-BRF--SchoolDrug-Law     10-21 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--School Drug-Law,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds School Distance Law for Drug Dealers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The distance between a school yard and a drug
dealer is measured in a straight line, a federal appeals court
ruled.
   The 9th Circuit Court of Appeals on Friday rejected the claim of
a convicted drug dealer that a federal law imposing strict
penalties for drug peddling within 1,000 feet of a school should be
measured by how far children would have to walk to the crime scene.
   Everton Gladstone Watson was convicted of selling marijuana at a
market about 960 feet from an elementary school, said his lawyer,
Michael Brush.
   Students would have had to walk more than 1,000 feet from the
school to reach Watson, Brush said.
   But the appeals court ruled that a straight line measurement
``creates a readily ascertainable zone of protection'' for children.
   Watson was sentenced last year to two years in prison under the
law, which imposes a minimum one-year sentence.
</TEXT>
