<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Economic     10-21 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Economic,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethnic Disoutes, Strikes Halved Economic Growth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic growth was cut almost in half this year
by lower production, strikes and ethnic unrest, while foreign trade
and consumer prices were higher, a government official said.
   Growth was 2.4 percent in the first nine months of 1989,
compared to 4.7 percent in the same period last year, said Nikolai
G. Belov, deputy chairman of the State Committee for Statistics.
   ``Negative tendencies were notably on an increase from July to
September, caused mostly by the weakening of production discipline,
ethnic conflicts and strikes,'' the official Tass news agency
quoted Belov as saying.
   Soviet coal miners walked of their jobs this summer demanding
better working conditions. They also made political demands.
   Local ethnic disputes brought on strikes in factories in the
republics of Azerbaijan, Moldavia and Estonia. Last month Armenia's
economy largely shut down after an Azerbaijani rail blockade cut
off supplies of fuel, food and building materials in a dispute over
a territory both republics claim.
   Consumer prices rose 2.6 percent so far this year and demand
remains greater than supply, Belov said.
   ``There has been a 5.7 percent increase in consumer goods, lower
than the plan, which called for 10 percent,'' he said.
   In the first nine months, foreign trade grew by 2.8 percent and
all but 0.5 percent of it was increased imports, Belov said.
   Belov said the number of foreign companies forming joint
ventures with Soviet companies grew to 936 involving 53 different
countries and employ 15,000 people, Soviet and foreign.
   Agriculture officials anticipate an improved grain harvest this
year, Belov said. He gave the harvest figure to date as about 209
million tons, compared with 195 million tons at this time last year.
   In Washington, the U.S. Agriculture Department said the Soviet
Union was continuing to buy large amounts of grain from the United
States.
   It said sales for 1988-89 were more about 21.7 million tons _
16.3 million tons of corn and 5.4 million tons of wheat. In
addition, sales included 442,500 tons of soybeans, 1.35 million
tons of soybean meal and 1.02 million tons of grain sorghums.
</TEXT>
