<SECOND>PM-Japan-Earthquake Aid,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Cities, Companies Send Aid to San Francisco</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese companies, citizens' groups and local
governments have pledged hundreds of thousands of dollars for
victims of the San Francisco area earthquake.
   Both Sumitomo Bank and Toyota Motor Corp.'s U.S. subsidiary said
they were each donating $500,000 to victims of Tuesday's temblor,
which measured 6.1 on the Richter scale.
   The city of Tokyo sent $15,000 each to San Francisco and
Oakland, Foreign Ministry spokesman Taizo Watanabe said Friday.
Osaka, Japan's second-largest city, gave $10,000 to San Francisco
and its sister city, while Yokohama gave $10,000 to each of the
U.S. cities.
   The Japanese archipelago lies along one of the world's most
active seismic areas and earthquakes are commonplace. The 1923
earthquake that destroyed Tokyo and killed 140,000 is etched in
Japanese memories.
   Newspapers reported other corporate donations which could not be
immediately confirmed because of the weekend holiday.
   Hitachi, the electronics giant, and two other companies in the
Hitachi group gave $180,000, while Fujitsu, an electronics and
computer manufacturer donated $100,000 and 200 cellular telephones,
the reports said. Mitsubishi International Corp., sent $100,000,
they said.
   In addition, U.S. Kawasaki Motors donated $50,000 in
power-generating equipment to ease power shortages in San
Francisco, the reports said.
   Japan's Federation of Economic Organizations, a grouping of
powerful business associations, began a fund-raising campaign for
quake victims, Foreign Ministry spokesman Watanabe said.
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party also said it would start
a campaign within the party and among the public for the victims,
Foreign Minister Taro Nakayama said.
   The Japanese Red Cross has given $35,700 to its American
counterpart in emergency aid, while the America-Japan Society has
set up an account asking for donations from the public, Watanabe
said.
</TEXT>
