<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 0850EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Markets-Brady 1stLd-Writethru a0430 10-21 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets-Brady, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0430,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brady: Central Regulation Needed For All Financial Markets</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 3rd graf bgng ``As senior administration ... '' to restore
dropped word ``officials.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady says Bush
administration officials knew before stock market trading began
last Monday they likely weren't facing a repeat of the 1987 crash.
   ``I don't think anybody had an air of panic,'' Brady said Friday
in his first extensive public discussion of the sudden, 190-point
drop in the Dow Jones industrial average on Oct. 13.
   As senior administration officials gathered at the White House
at 7 a.m. Monday, the first trading day after the plunge, they
focused on the reaction of foreign markets, which had been closed
during the Friday the 13th plummet, he said.
   ``It became clear as I stared at those statistics that it looked
much more like a technical market change. ... (The U.S. stock
decline) was picked up around the rest of the world, but not added
to. That is an important distinction,'' he said in an interview.
   From the White House, Brady went to the Treasury Building and
personally monitored developments on computer screens providing
up-to-date information simultaneously on stocks, stock futures,
international currency and bond trading, he said.
   The market sharply recovered Monday, rising 88 points. For the
week, it regained 120 points.
   ``You shouldn't look at this loss on Friday as some cataclysmic
event, but more of an instantaneous technical reaction,'' he said.
   Two years earlier, the story was different. The market fell more
than 100 points on a Friday, then crashed 508 points the next
trading day, which became known as Black Monday.
   The Treasury secretary, who as a private citizen headed a
presidential commission that investigated the 1987 crash, said top
administration officials had learned from the past.
   This time, officials were better prepared to coordinate their
actions and statements and had much more sophisticated means of
monitoring markets.
   Brady declined to say precisely what he would propose when he
testifies next week in Congress. But he left little doubt that he
hasn't changed his mind about the steps he recommended two years
ago.
   ``With all due modesty, I might say there's been nothing written
since that contravenes any of the information in the report. So
it's, in a certain sense, a guide to what happened then and what
you might need to do now,'' he said.
   Among the recommendations then was that a single agency,
probably the Federal Reserve, coordinate regulation of all
financial markets.
   ``The more progress we can make towards bringing the regulation
into one place, or to bring it into a high degree of coordination,
the better off we're going to be at it,'' he said.
   Then a Wall Street investment banker, Brady was widely praised
for his report, although the Reagan administration failed to adopt
many of its recommendations.
   Brady, assisted by two Harvard professors who are now senior
deputies at Treasury, concluded the stock market in New York and
the futures markets in Chicago, and to a degree stock and futures
markets worldwide, function as one market because of the speed of
electronic communication and computer-executed trading.
   ``The implication of the conclusion that we had one market would
indicate that too many different regulators for that one market
don't make an awful lot of sense,'' he said.
   Then as now, the Securities and Exchange Commission oversaw
stock and options markets, the Commodity Futures Trading Commission
regulated futures markets and the Federal Reserve Board set stock
margins and supervised the payments system among banks and
brokerage houses.
   But Brady acknowledged the political difficulty of disturbing
regulatory turf that was divided years ago. After the 1987 crash,
traders on the Chicago futures markets and the members of Congress
who represent them resisted any changes in the regulatory lineup.
   ``Those geographic markets have their constituencies and they
don't want to be changed,'' Brady said. ``That doesn't mean that
they shouldn't be.''
   The Reagan administration did establish a working group through
which the various agency heads could coordinate policy, although
none of the regulators have the power to impose their views on the
others. It continues to operate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
