<FIRST>u i PM-EastGermany 3rdLd-Writethru a0484 10-21 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Germany, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0484,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Urges Refugees to Return; Thousands Demonstrate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with police chief pledging
to investigate police brutality; picks up 6th pvs, ``We want...'; edits
throughout to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people clutched candles and called
for reform during a late-night vigil in Dresden. The government
took a more tolerant line against such protests today, promising to
probe charges of police brutality at earlier rallies for democracy.
   East Germany's official ADN news agency said the candlelight
demonstration was held after Lutheran church services in Dresden
late Friday. Pro-democracy activists estimated the crowd at 50,000,
but Lutheran church sources and ADN said 20,000 participated.
   ADN said there was no trouble at the rally, the latest in a
series of protests held by an increasingly vocal populace unhappy
with their government's strict adherence to socialism.
   ADN reported that the deputy police chief in East Berlin pledged
to investigate all allegations of police brutality during mass
demonstrations two weeks ago.
   Dieter Dietze was quoted as saying 60 complaints had been filed
and they all would be ``thoroughly investigated.''
   Police used force to break up pro-democracy protests that swept
the nation two weeks ago, but have shown restraint since then.
   On Friday, East German officials appealed to tens of thousands
of those who have fled West to return home. Spokesman Wolfgang
Meyer said East Berlin's diplomatic missions would help East
Germans return home as quickly as possible.
   ``We want to help anyone, unless there are reasons to prevent
it, to come back home,'' Meyer said, without elaborating.
   The message was in sharp contrast to previous government
statements denouncing those who took part in the exodus.
   More than 55,000 East Germans have fled West in recent months,
discouraged by the Stalinist social restrictions placed on them
when other East European nations are moving toward democracy.
   Hard-line leader Erich Honecker, who had resisted reforms, was
replaced by his protege, Egon Krenz, on Wednesday after 18 years in
power. Krenz is also an orthodox proponent of strict party rule,
but he has sought to project a willingess for reforms as long as
the Communist Party's leading role is not challenged.
   Since Krenz's takeover, state-run media have embarked on an
unprecedented course of more critical reporting on economic and
political problems.
   Meanwhile, a West German official rejected conditions set by
Krenz for the possible loosening of travel for East Germans to the
West.
   Krenz said Thursday that a new law would be drafted to expand
East Germans' travel rights but made it clear that substantial
economic and political hurdles stood in the way of letting everyone
travel West.
   Many East Germans say a lack of travel freedom is the hard to
bear in the tightly-controlled society. It has, in part, fueled the
exodus West.
   But Krenz said the biggest obstacle to freer travel is West
Germany's refusal to recognize East German citizenship.
   East German leaders say economic problems also pose considerable
obstacles, because East Germans need convertible currency to travel
in the West.
   Dorothee Wilms, who heads West Germany's Ministry for
Inter-German Relations, said Bonn will not change its position on
the East German citizenship issue and charged that East Berlin
already receives millions of dollars' worth of hard currency from
West Germany.
   ``If East German officials really want to allow their citizens
free travel to the West, then they should use some of this money,''
Ms. Wilms said in an interview with West Germany's ZDF television
network.
   East German marks are not convertible to currencies traded on
international markets and therefore have no real value in the West.
</TEXT>
