<FIRST>r i PM-NIreland-Ambush     10-21 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NIreland-Ambush,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Policeman, Injure Another in Country Ambush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen ambushed a police car in
South Armagh province, killing one officer and injuring another,
police said today.
   The Irish Republican Army in South Armagh claimed responsibility
for the ambush in Belleek, about 10 miles north of the border with
the Irish Republic.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary, the province's police force, said
the unmarked, armored police car came under heavy caliber
machine-gun fire as it drove down the main street of Belleek, where
the officers had an appointment.
   The car was riddled with bullets, burst into flames and was
completely burned, police said.
   Constable Michael Marshall, 25, who was married and had two
daughters, died instantly, police said. His 21-year-old colleague,
who was not identified, was seriously injured in the legs and a
shoulder.
   Marshall was the eighth member of the Royal Ulster Constabulary
to be killed by the IRA in Northern Ireland this year and the 265th
to die in 20 years of violence in the province.
   Predominantly Roman Catholic South Armagh is an IRA stronghold
known as bandit country by security forces in the province.
   The mainly Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Northern Ireland and unite the predominantly Protestant province
with the 95 percent Catholic Republic of Ireland under socialist
rule.
   In another incident, police said an explosion Saturday morning
damaged the telephone exchange at Mill Hill, Castlewellen in the
southeastern part of the province but nobody was injured.
</TEXT>
