<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica     10-21 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Approves First African National Congress Rally in 29 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activists today said the government
will allow seven freed black prisoners to appear at a rally of the
outlawed African National Congress.
   No African National Congress rally has been allowed in South
Africa since the organization was banned in 1960.
   Eight prominent black prisoners, many of them jailed in excess
of 25 years, were freed by the government on Sunday. Seven were
African National Congress leaders.
   Activists said those seven will appear at the Oct. 29 rally in
Soweto that is being billed as an African National Congress event.
   ``Apart from being a welcoming party, the rally is going to be
an occasion at which our leaders will be making a major address to
the nation on a whole range of issues,'' National Union of
Mineworkers secretary-general Cyril Ramaphosa said at a news
conference near the home of Walter Sisulu, one of the freed
prisoners.
   The black, green, and gold African National Congress flag flew
from a pole above Sisulu's roof. He and some of the other recently
freed prisoners met today with Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu at
a birthday celebration for Sisulu's activist wife, Albertina, 72.
   Ramaphosa said the group had not sought government permission
for the rally, to be held at noon Oct. 29 in a new soccer stadium
near Soweto. But he said letters had been sent to President F.W. de
Klerk, the minister of justice and the chief magistrate of
Johannesburg informing them of the plans.
   The Department of Justice issued a statement late Friday night
saying an application to hold the meeting had been approved by the
chief magistrate.
   Informed of the approval during the news conference, Ramaphosa
said, ``They approved it because they knew we would give them
trouble if they didn't.''
   ``This will be the first rally of leaders of the African
National Congress in nearly 30 years,'' said Murphy Morobe,
spokesman for the banned United Democratic Front. ``Comrade Walter
Sisulu will deliver a major address to the nation.''
   Ramaphosa said the group had asked the government to lift
restrictions on former African National Congress national chairman
Govan Mbeki so that he could join his colleagues at the rally.
   Mbeki was freed from prison in 1987, but the government banned
two rallies he was to address, then restricted him to his hometown
near Port Elizabeth and prohibited him from speaking in public or
talking to the press.
   De Klerk said that if there was some guarantee from
``organizations which practiced a policy of political violence and
acts of terror'' that such things would not recur, it would improve
the atmosphere in which the 3-year-old national emergency could be
lifted.
   De Klerk has preached conciliation with the black majority since
he was elected in August. He has promised to gradually bring blacks
into the political process in South Africa, where the white
minority holds all power.
   Several rallies that normally would have been broken up by
police have been allowed to take place in recent weeks.
</TEXT>
