<FIRST>u i PM-TyphoonElsie 3rdLd-Writethru a0478 10-21 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Typhoon Elsie, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0478,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>17 Dead In Typhoon In Northern Philippines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with more than 300,000 in government
shelters. Pick up 5th pvs, `Capt. Donna...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Typhoon Elsie headed for China's
southern island province of Hainan today after killing at least 17
people in the northern Philippines and forcing more than 300,000
into government shelters, officials said.
   The Manila weather bureau said Elsie was packing winds of 127
mph when it blew ashore Thursday but had since weakened to 75 mph.
If Elsie maintains its westward course at 11 mph, it will hit
Hainan by Monday, said meteorologist Felio Bartolome.
   A compilation of reports from the Red Cross and the military's
Office of Civil Defense showed 10 people died in Isabela province,
four in Quirino province, two in La Union province and one in
Benguet province. Most of the dead either drowned or were hit by
falling trees and flying galvanized iron roofing.
   Officials added 15 people were injured and more than 326,800
others were taking temporary refuge in government shelters. More
than 5,000 houses were either destroyed or damaged, they added.
   Capt. Donna Eggleston, a U.S. Air Force spokeswoman, said Clark
Air Base had minimal damage as Typhoon Elsie spared Pampanga
province, 50 miles north of Manila, from the brunt of its
destructive winds.
   Wallace Air Station, a joint Philippine-U.S. air defense radar
complex in La Union, suffered damages worth $20,000 and the rest
and recreation facility, Camp John Hay, had about $10,000 in
damage, mostly caused by detached roofs.
   Officials said many northern provinces lost electricity when
high winds toppled power lines. Fallen trees littered the national
highway and blocked dozens of other roads.
   Civil defense said Elsie's winds caused two tugboats to sink and
a British-registered yacht to slam into port at La Union's Poro
Point, but there were no immediate reports of casualties on the
vessels.
   An average of 20 typhoons and tropical storms strike the
Philippines annually. Elsie is the 17th this year.
   Manila newspapers reported today that U.S. pop-rock star Cyndi
Lauper, who was in Manila last week for a two-day concert, last
Sunday donated $2,300 to typhoon victims.
   On Oct. 10, Tropical storm Dan hit Manila and southern Luzon on
Oct. 10, killing at least 59 people. Typhoon Angela killed at least
119 people in northern Luzon four days earlier.
</TEXT>
