<FIRST>r i AM-India-Sikhs     10-21 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Sikhs,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Sikhs Sentenced to Death for Killing Army General</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Saturday sentenced two Sikhs to
death for killing India's most decorated military hero, who
commanded the army when it stormed Sikhism's holiest shrine in 1984
to drive out Sikh militants.
   Judge V.L. Rukar found Sukhdev Singh and Harjinder Singh guilty
of murdering Arun S. Vaidya in August 1986. Rukar acquitted a third
Sikh, Nirmal Singh, for lack of evidence.
   The verdict was announced in the central Indian city of Poona,
where Vaidya was slain after retiring from the army.
   Rukar said the convicted men should be hanged, but he ordered
that the sentences be confirmed by India's Supreme Court.
   Vaidya was targeted by Sikh militants because he was the chief
of the Indian army when it stormed the Golden Temple in Amritsar in
June 1984. At least 1,200 people, mostly Sikhs, were killed in the
operation.
   The Khalistan Commando Force, an underground Sikh group, claimed
responsibility for the general's assassination.
   Sikhs make up about 2 percent of India's 880 million people, and
militants have been campaigning since 1982 for an independent Sikh
nation. They claim they are discriminated against by Hindus, who
account for 82 percent of India's population.
</TEXT>
