<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Violence Claims 11 Lives in Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese radicals detonated buried
explosives under a military truck in southern Sri Lanka on
Saturday, killing five soldiers and wounding 10 others, army
officials said.
   Elsewhere, at least six people, including three radicals, were
killed, said the officials.
   The attack on the soldiers occurred in Hambantota district, 105
miles southeast of Colombo.
   In central and southern Sri Lanka, government troops shot and
killed three radicals in separate incidents Friday, said the
military officials who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Sinhalese radicals also hacked to death three civilians in
Baddula district, 80 miles east of Colombo.
   Sinhalese radicals started their campaign of violence two years
ago, when the Sri Lankan government signed a peace accord to end
the war by militant Tamils.
   The radicals say the accord offered too many concessions to the
Tamils, who make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
Sinhalese form about 75 percent of the country's population.
   Tamils claim they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese in
government jobs, education and in the army.
   At least 11,000 people have been killed since Tamil rebel took
up arms in 1983. Another 5,000 people have died in the Sinhalese
backlash.
