<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 1130EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Cheney     10-21 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cheney,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Secretary Embarking On Three-Week Global Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, setting off on
a three-week tour of key allied capitals and U.S. military posts,
says East-West negotiations on slashing conventional forces are
going so well that an agreement is possible ``in the
not-too-distant future.''
   Cheney was departing Saturday for a trip that will take him to
France, Great Britain, West Germany and Italy, with a stop in
Portugal for NATO talks, as well as meetings in Australia and
Hawaii.
   Forging an approach to the sweeping changes in the Soviet Union
and Eastern Europe, and discussing with his NATO counterparts the
Vienna talks on conventional force reductions, are high on the
agenda at many of Cheney's sessions, Pentagon officials say.
   In an interview with The Associated Press shortly before he left
on his first major excursion as defense secretary, Cheney observed
that the negotiations between North Atlantic Treaty Organization
members and the Warsaw Pact are ``moving along in pretty good
shape.''
   ``There are still a lot of issues to work out, but I think there
is a sincere desire on the part of virtually everybody, including
the Soviets. I am fairly optimistic we will get a good agreement
... in the not-too-distant future,'' Cheney said.
   While problems remain in verification and counting aircraft, ``I
think we're talking about a year or two at most'' for reaching a
full agreement, he said.
   Cheney said another item under constant discussion is
burden-sharing, and he spoke of the pressures against increases in
military spending for the United States and its Western European
allies.
   ``As convictions grow that Mr. (Mikhail) Gorbachev and the
Soviets ... don't constitute the threat they used to, it's more and
more difficult to get people to allocate the same levels of
resources to their defense budget _ and that affects the kind of
decisions we have to make,'' Cheney said.
   The allies would be ``prepared to allocate much higher levels of
resources'' if the Soviets were pursuing a policy more hostile to
the West, or more intolerant of the changes under way in Poland,
Hungary and East Germany, he said.
   Cheney added that ``while it is perhaps more difficult to
maintain alliance cohesion and unity at a time when there is this
perception that the threat is significantly reduced, if anything it
is more important.''
   The United States allocates about 60 percent of its conventional
forces budget to the defense of Western Europe _ a situation that
prompts criticism among some lawmakers who have called for fewer
expenditures for such economically well-off nations.
   ``We've maintained our commitments, and we are encourage our
allies to do the same,'' Cheney said.
   The former Wyoming congressman is leaving as his negotiations
over the Pentagon's fiscal 1990 budget have stalemated, in part
over Cheney's demands that lawmakers do away with several weapons
systems.
   Cheney noted that he had twice postponed the trip and couldn't
avoid being out of Washington for three full weeks, given that he
was is also scheduled to attend an annual ministerial conference
with Australian officials.
   ``We've got good communications, so we can manage to maintain
our involvement with major issues, the budget, and so forth,'' he
said.
   Cheney will meet with his counterparts in Paris on Sunday, and
then travels on Monday to Vilamoura, Portugal, for two days of NATO
discussions with defense ministers.
   He travels to England on Wednesday, where he will visit with a
U.S. Air Force unit and have meetings with British officials. On
Thursday, he meets in Bonn with Defense Minister Gerhard
Stoltenberg and goes on to Berlin and sessions with Army troops.
   Cheney is slated to travel to Rome on Saturday, where he will
spend three days and visit ships from the U.S. Sixth Fleet.
   During the Pacific leg of the trip in the first week of
November, Cheney will join Secretary of State James A. Baker III
for the annual session with Australian officials.
   Afterwards, he is scheduled to visit U.S. naval facilities and
consult in Hawaii with Adm. Huntington Hardisty, the
commander-in-chief of U.S. forces in the Pacfic.
   He is slated to return to Washington Nov. 10.
</TEXT>
