<DOCNO> AP891021-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 1220EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Opera     10-21 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Opera,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Show Goes On _ With Costumes, But Not Scenery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD BLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was fallen plaster in the War
Memorial Opera House and the building was unsafe for the public, so
the San Francisco Opera moved a performance for the first time in
its 67-year history.
   Instead of performing Verdi's ``Otello'' in the ornate opera
house beside City Hall, the company prsented a semi-staged version
in the Masonic Auditorium atop Nob Hill. It was the company's first
performance since Tuesday's earthquake.
   ``It was a great experience,'' said soprano Katia Ricciarelli,
who sang Desdemona. ``It was like the (Franco) Zeffirelli film. You
are so close you just use emotion. You don't have to use such big
movements.''
   Jean-Pierre Ponnelle's scenery was left at the opera house,
which still needs several days of cleanup. But the performers wore
costumes and the supertitles were taken along, too.
   The Masonic Auditorium is much more intimate than the 3,252-seat
War Memorial. Even though it has only 87 fewer seats, the entire
hall is only slightly larger than the stage of New York's
Metropolitan Opera House.
   Two more semi-staged performances are scheduled for the Masonic
Auditorium this weekend _ the season premiere of Verdi's ``Aida''
on Saturday and Mozart's ``Idomeneo'' on Sunday. The company
intends to return to the War Memorial on Tuesday for the final
``Otello.''
   When Tuesday performance of ``Idomeneo'' was canceled following
the quake, it was the second canceled performance in the company's
history. The first was after President Kennedy's assassination on
Nov. 22, 1963.
   The performers got just one hour of rehearsal in the new
auditorium and Kazimierz Kord, the conductor, was unsure of the
acoustics.
   ``We are just happy we can do it,'' the maestro said.
   Before the performance, San Francisco Opera general director
Lotfi Mansouri addressed the audience of about 1,000.
   ``We all have so much to be thankful for,'' he said. ``At the
same time, our thoughts are with the people who shouldered the
burden this week.''
   Joanne Dunne of San Rafael, Calif., a subscriber for 25 years,
was impressed by the way the company pressed ahead despite the
tragedy.
   ``We're hearty souls,'' she said.
   But her daughter, Laurie, would have preferred ``Otello'' at the
War Memorial.
   ``I'd much rather have it in the Opera House with the costumes
on stage and the champagne downstairs,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891021-0097 </DOCNO>
