<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every four hours, the 10 officers on duty
at the missing persons bureau of the Oakland police check their
list to determine if anyone has turned up after being reported as
missing in the earthquake.
   ``A lot of times they don't call us back when someone has shown
up,'' said Sgt. Greg Hughes, who heads the bureau. ``When we
contact them, usually they say, `You know, I was just going to call
you.'''
   Since Tuesday night, 250 people have been reported missing in
connection with the quake. By Friday evening, 164 had been located,
alive or dead. More than 30 victims have been pulled from the
wreckage of collapsed Interstate 880.
   That left 86 still missing, all of whom, reports indicated, had
a chance of driving on the double-decker freeway when it collapsed,
trapping cars in the rubble.
   ``Most of the calls to us are coming from out of state,'' Hughes
said. ``We're isolating and screening reports so make sure we don't
include someone who just hasn't seen their Aunt Tilley in four
months.''
   Officer Gary Foppiana said all the people believed missing from
the earthquake can be traced to the freeway collapse and most are
from the Bay area.
   ``Occasionally an officer will call us to give a license plate
from out there,'' Foppiana said of the crushed cars being pulled
from the collapsed freeway.
   One of the missing is Melissa Maxwell, a deputy district
attorney for Alameda County.
   She left her office, next to another stretch of the fateful
freeway, on Tuesday afternoon for the San Francisco airport to pick
up some relatives and hasn't been heard from since, said Senior
Deputy District Attorney John Adams.
   ``They found some cars and one of them looked like hers,'' Adams
said. ``We're hoping for the best, but who knows?''
   Foppiana said the count had been complicated by the fact that
some of the dead were never reported missing.
   That's why police are regularly calling everyone who has made a
report.
   ``It's not like an air crash, where people are international,''
said Hughes. ``You have people, working stiffs, living in the East
Bay or the city (San Francisco).
   ``There's a lot of people close to home.''
