<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--MalpracticeSuit     10-21 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Malpractice Suit,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Awards $5.1 Million to 8-Year-Old, Parents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury awarded $5.1 million in damages to an
8-year-old and his parents, who sued the child's pediatrician
charging that his treatment of their son's broken arm caused the
boy to lose the use of the arm.
   C. Stephen Hauptli broke his left arm five years ago after
falling off his parents' brass bed and catching his arm in the
footboard, according to state district court records.
   Dr. George Monroe and an orthopedic consultant, Dr. Harry Dubow,
treated the boy at Humana Hospital-Medical City Dallas.
   The Dallas County jury found last week that despite the child's
screams and fever, the doctors failed to detect complications
resulting from a decrease of blood flow in the injured arm. This
resulted in a permanent deterioration and loss of muscle use or
movement.
   Dubow and the hospital's parent company, Humana Health Care,
recently settled out of court with the plaintiffs for $700,000.
