<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 1354EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PaAbortion     10-21 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pa Abortion,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Question Finally Comes to Vote in Pennsylvania</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE McGRAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One Pennsylvania lawmaker received
gruesome pictures of aborted fetuses in the mail, while another was
accused of maintaining an unholy alliance with the pope.
   As the Legislature prepares to vote on a stringent package of
abortion restrictions this week, protesters have hung metal hangers
on the walls of legislators' district offices, conducted
candlelight vigils, picketed lawmakers when they spoke at almost
any kind of appearance, and sent mail by the truckload.
   When the vote is taken Tuesday, the traditionally anti-abortion
Legislature could become the first in the nation to adopt abortion
restrictions since the Supreme Court allowed states more latitude
in restricting abortions in July. An effort to pass new
restrictions fell short in the Florida legislature earlier this
month. Gov. Robert P. Casey has said he will sign the bill.
   Pro-choice lawmakers, who hold a minority in both the House and
Senate here, plan to fight the proposed restrictions and also will
try to loosen current regulations.
   The Missouri measures upheld by the Supreme Court ruling July 3
ban abortions in public hospitals, stop public employees from
counseling women about abortions, and require doctors performing
abortions to first test any fetus over 20 weeks old to determine if
it could live outside the womb.
   The anti-abortion legislation before the Pennsylvania
Legislature would ban abortions after the 24th week of pregnancy
except to save the life of the mother, prohibit abortions based on
a fetus' sex, require women to inform their husbands if they plan
to get an abortion, and require a 24-hour waiting period. The
legislation also would ban experiments done with the tissue of an
aborted fetus, except to save its life.
   Last year, Casey vetoed anti-abortion legislation, saying he
opposes abortion but didn't think it would survive a court
challenge. But in light of the Supreme Court decision, Casey said
he believed the current legislation would withstand a court fight.
   Rep. Stephen Freind, a suburban Philadelphia Republican and the
Legislature's chief abortion opponent, said he hopes to get his
proposed restrictions passed as an amendment to a bill now before
the House that would toughen penalties for incest. He said he
thought the measure could be passed more quickly that way, rather
than having the restrictions considered in a separate bill.
   Rep. Karen Ritter, a Democrat from the Lehigh Valley who leads
the House pro-choice caucus, said lobbying from both sides has been
intense.
   ``I got a postcard from a priest with a picture of a mutilated
fetus. It said, `I'm praying for your soul to come back to
Christ,''' she said.
   Anti-abortion supporters have vowed to bump her from the seat
she has held since 1987. Her father, James Ritter, held the same
seat from 165 to 1982 and received similar pressure, she said.
   Chris McNally, a freshman Democrat from Allegheny County, said
he is taking the 1,000 hangers taped to his office last week by
pro-choice advocates and using them in an impromptu clothing drive.
The hangers have become the symbol of the pro-choice movement
because they signify how some women were forced to abort their
fetuses before abortion became legal.
   ``I think it's great; people ought to lobby like this for every
issue. There's a lot of other issues that are very important and I
wish people would be more active on those,'' McNally said.
   An ardent opponent of abortion, Rep. Gerard Kosinski, said his
most memorable communication with pro-choice advocates was a letter
chastising him ``for taking orders from the Vatican.''
   ``As yet, I'm still awaiting a call from the pope,'' Kosinski
said.
   So far this fall, abortion opponents have made little headway in
state capitals or in Congress. In Austin, Texas, on Friday, Gov.
Bill Clements stunned anti-abortion leaders when he announced that
abortion restrictions will not appear on an agenda of an upcoming
special legislative session.
   Clements said the Nov. 14 special session will be limited to
workers' compensation reform.
   Clements' spokeswoman said she didn't think the governor was
swayed by recent events in Florida, where the Legislature rejected
in two days all abortion restrictions proposed by Gov. Bob Martinez.
</TEXT>
