<FIRST>u i PM-Honduras-PlaneCrash 4thLd-Writethru   10-21 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honduras-Plane Crash, 4th Ld - Writethru,a0552,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Passenger Plane Crashes in Honduras</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to UPDATE with at least 40 dead, changes
passenger figures; picks up 6th pvs: Regalado Hernandez .. .</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Honduran Boeing 727 carrying 137
people smashed into a mountain region just south of Tegucigalpa
early today, officials said. At least 40 people were reported
killed.
   Radio HRN, a privately owned station, said 40 bodies had been
recovered from the site, about 25 miles south of the capital, and
another 20 injured had been rescued about four hours after the
crash.
   Earlier reports from the Tegucigalpa fire department indicated
that 60 people had been rescued. Red Cross and fire officials said
rescuers were still searching the wreckage.
   Those rescued all were hosptalized with serious burns,
firefighters and Red Cross workers said.
   The SAHSA airline passenger jet crashed at about 7:45 a.m. in
the mountain region of Las Tablitas, about 25 miles south of the
capital, said Gen. Humberto Regalado Hernandez, the armed forces
chief.
   A SAHSA airline employee, who insisted on anonymity, said there
were 129 passengers and eight crew on board the plane when it
crashed. Earlier, airline officials had said there was a total of
143 people on board.
   Red Cross workers said a majority of the victims were suffering
from serious burn.
   Control tower employees at Tocontin Airport, who insisted on
anonymity, said unusually strong winds were blowing at the time the
aircraft was trying to land.
   Regalado Hernandez said he ordered military and civilian rescue
crews to the area as well as a number of air force helicopters.
Aviation routes in Honduras are controlled by the military.
   The plane was on a regular run from San Jose, the capital of
Costa Rica, to Tegucigalpa's Tocontin Airport with a stop in
Managua, the Nicaraguan capital.
   Nicaragua's Voice of Nicaragua said about 100 passengers, most
of them Nicaraguans, boarded the plane in Managua airport but gave
no details.
   Regalado Hernandez said that from reports he received he
believed the plane crashed at the foot of a mountain called Cerro
Hules. He said he had no further details.
</TEXT>
