<DOCNO> AP891021-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 1418EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-EastBlocAid     10-21 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Bloc Aid,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poles Press for More U.S. Aid, West Sees Larger European Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poland is pressing President Bush to
lead relief efforts for its new non-Communist government, but
Western leaders have made clear they see the matter as primarily
Europe's responsibility.
   Participants at last week's East-West security conference in
Frankfurt, called ``Security in the 1990s,'' indicated they will
continue to approach financial aid for reform-oriented East
European states as in the security interests of all Western nations.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government already has promised more
than $1 billion in debt relief to Poland, and projects to aid
Hungary in its move toward a multiparty democracy are also in the
works in advance of Kohl's visit to Budapest in December.
   The Group of Seven wealthy democracies decided at their summit
in Paris in July to coordinate aid to Poland and Hungary through
the European Economic Community based in Brussels, Belgium.
   Poland, however, would like to see Washington lead the effort.
   ``It's soon to become a question of whether we have a Marshall
Plan or martial law,'' said Dariusz K. Rosati, director of Warsaw's
Foreign Trade Research Institute.
   ``I say this to help visualize the dramatic choice facing the
Western side,'' he said in an interview.
   The Marshall Plan was a broad U.S.-financed aid program that
helped West Germany rebuild itself into an economic powerhouse
after the destruction of World War II.
   Some West German politicians have suggested a similar relief
effort be organized for Poland and Hungary to help rebuild
economies that have been ravaged by four decades of socialism.
   ``If there is no substantial improvement in the market situation
within a few months, no one _ not even the Mazowiecki government _
will be able to control what happens,'' Rosati said, referring to
the new leadership of Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki, a former
Solidarity journalist.
   Rosati said the Bush government should do the most ``because the
United States has always played a leading role in supporting change
in Poland.''
   But he acknowledged that European efforts have been swifter and
more comprehensive in organizing food aid and debt relief for
Poland.
   Bush has pledged $200 million in aid to Poland in conjunction
with a Western fund being set up to help the new Warsaw government.
   The U.S. House of Representatives substantially upped Bush's aid
offer with its approval Thursday of $837 million in support for
Hungary and Poland. But the package still awaits Senate approval,
and the White House has suggested the sum may be excessive.
   Kohl's chief foreign affairs adviser, Horst Teltschik, has said
the chancellor plans to guarantee during his visit to Warsaw in
mid-November that the aid pool will reach $1 billion _ effectively
promising whatever West German contribution is needed to reach that
level.
   U.S. Commerce Secretary Robert A. Mosbacher told participants at
the security conference Thursday that Eastern Europe's economic
problems are ``home-grown'' and can be overcome only by
wide-ranging internal changes.
   ``Only the marketplace, only free enterprise, can solve the
desperate economic problems of the Eastern countries,'' Mosbacher
told the delegates in Frankfurt.
   Polish participants complained his views were short-sighted and
failed to address how Poland should get through the difficult
transition period.
   Rosati said inflation is spiraling and could soon overwhelm the
patience of Poles if they begin to see the turn toward democracy as
costing them food and economic stability.
   West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher reiterated
Bonn's view that financial aid for reformist states like Poland and
Hungary is a crucial means of maintaining political and military
stability in Europe in a period of rapid change.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
