<DOCNO> AP891021-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 1424EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Miami'sRiotTrial Bjt   10-21 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miami's Riot Trial, Bjt,0775</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miami Braces For Policeman's Trial in Shooting That Triggered Riots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Community leaders in this racially tense city are
bracing for the trial of a police officer in the shooting death of
a black motorcyclist that touched off riots in January.
   Acquittals of police officers in the deaths of blacks sparked
violence in Miami in 1980 and 1984. The impeachment conviction
Friday of a popular black federal judge, a heated local election
campaign and the drug war add kindling for catastrophe.
   Suspended Miami officer William E. Lozano is charged with
manslaughter in the Jan. 16 shooting of Clement Lloyd in a police
chase. After Lloyd was shot, his motorcycle crashed and passenger
Allan Blanchard was fatally injured.
   Jury selection begins Monday in Circuit Court unless Lozano's
attorneys succeed in getting the trial moved.
   The proceedings will be watched carefully by Miami's blacks, who
on Friday saw U.S. District Judge Alcee Hastings removed by the
Senate for bribery conspiracy six years after his acquittal in a
jury trial. Black reaction was angry but peaceful, and an upbeat
Hastings announced he will run for governor.
   Nevertheless, community leaders say the removal of Florida's
first black U.S. district judge adds to tensions fueled by a
campaign in which a Cuban-American is seeking a city commission
seat traditionally held by a black.
   Perceptions of political and judicial inequality, combined with
persistent problems of crime and poverty in the inner-city
neighborhoods, may need only a spark to flash into violence again,
some community leaders say.
   ``If too many of those things break together and appear to be
going against the black community, I think there could be a
demonstration of concern and anger,'' said Arthur Teele, a black
lawyer. ``To quote Dr. Martin Luther King, dark and difficult days
lie ahead.''
   Mayor Xavier Suarez said he doesn't think ``a Dante's Inferno
scenario'' will occur, although he and other city officials are
preparing for the possibility of riots if Lozano is acquitted.
   Lozano, boosted by fund-raising efforts on Spanish-language
radio in Miami and in Colombia for his defense, expressed
confidence last week.
   ``I'm innocent. What I did, I did in self-defense, and we're
going to prove that in court,'' said Lozano, who is of Colombian
descent.
   Defense attorneys Roy Black and Mark Seiden helped Miami officer
Luis Alvarez gain acquittal in 1984 for the fatal shooting of a
black youth. That verdict began two days of violence.
   In 1980, the acquittal of five Metro-Dade officers in the
beating death of a black motorcyclist sparked three days of bloody
rioting that killed 18 people.
   Police Chief Perry Anderson, who is black and was raised in
Miami's inner city, said most blacks he hears talking about the
case just want to see a fair trial. But he stills expects an
acquittal to mean trouble, in part because efforts to ease the
despair and frustration underlying the recurrent racial violence
have infringed on the profitable turfs of crack dealers.
   ``I know for a fact that the drug dealers are preparing to try
to cause problems, a riot,'' Anderson said. ``They like to see the
police in a hostile situation, the community hostile against the
police.''
   Unlike the sudden January disturbances, in which one person died
and 22 stores were burned, police this time have had months to
prepare. All 1,100 officers will be on call at the end of the
trial, expected to last about three weeks.
   The city has ordered 700 gas masks and has two armored personnel
carriers and National Guard military equipment available.
   The city has a clear mandate from people in Overtown, Liberty
City and other predominantly black neighborhoods not to allow
looting, Suarez said.
   Anderson said police will make arrests immediately, unlike in
January when they formed a perimeter and refrained from mass
arrests until the third day of violence. The trouble occurred the
week before the city was host to the Super Bowl.
   Because the trouble broke out on Martin Luther King Day, police
were reluctant to charge into a community whose holiday had been
disrupted by a police killing, Anderson said.
   ``You've got to utilize force, but you've also got to use
sensitivity,'' he said.
   A review panel set up after the January riots called on police
to improve recruitment and promotion of blacks. Anderson said the
police force is 19 percent black, up from 17 percent, and moving
toward a goal of 21 percent to match the percentage of blacks in
the city population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
