<DOCNO> AP891021-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 1439EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-SantaCruz Bjt   10-21 0872</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Santa Cruz, Bjt,0894</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors Near Epicenter: `Time for a Rebirth'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATSONVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chris Hervey started her week with an
office to go to each morning and a house to return to each night.
Now, she has neither.
   But she has no time for pouting or pity. ``I'm here,'' the
earthquake survivor said proudly. ``I think people are just happy
they're alive. Then you assess your losses. You take what you've
got and you go on.''
   It's a philosophy shared by many residents of Santa Cruz County,
as they recover, rebuild and rebound from the catastrophic quake
that shook their communities last week.
   ``Start all over. It's what you have to do,'' said John Kane,
who narrowly escaped death Tuesday as he watched from the doorway
while a stream of bricks tumbled from the top of the building that
houses his insurance business.
   ``You can't roll over and die,'' he said, surveying his office
equipment spread out in the rubble-strewn parking lot in the back
of the office building that has been condemned.
   ``It's time for a rebirth,'' he said.
   But he knows it won't be easy. ``I'm preparing myself for a lot
of problems and a lot of trials and a lot of frustrations,'' he
said.
   Others will be in the same predicament in this county where five
people died, hundreds of buildings were destroyed or damaged, and
thousands were left homeless. Some have ended up with the sky as a
roof, huddling in tents or sleeping bags in school grounds, parking
lots and back yards.
   Though some businesses have reopened and electricity has been
restored in many places, in towns such as Watsonville there still
are long lines for food, and mothers and their children walk the
streets carrying empty plastic jugs in search of water.
   Damage estimates already have reached the billion-dollar mark in
this county of 229,000 people. And the devastation is felt from the
rugged mountains near the epicenter of the quake where fissures
ripped open three-foot gashes in the earth, to the Pacific Garden
Mall in Santa Cruz where buildings split open like melons, to the
agricultural town of Watsonville, where a Victorian Gothic church
that survived the 1906 quake wasn't as lucky this time.
   For people in the county, this is only the latest assault by
nature. In recent years, there have been floods and fires _ and
fears of an earthquake.
   And if Tuesday's temblor wasn't bad enough, a series of
aftershocks frayed nerves and knocked down people trying to get
back on their feet.
   ``People say `I think I'm going to die,''' said crisis counselor
Rosa Zayas, who's been helping out at a 24-hour medical clinic in
Watsonville. ``People are sick, they're vomiting, they're confused.
They're not sure it's stopped.''
   Miss Hervey, for one, said the aftershocks were so big that when
her hands began trembling, ``you couldn't tell if it was nerves,
your pulse or the earthquake.''
   Her house has been condemned, and she said she has slept
outside, taking her 86-year-old grandmother with her. ``You sleep
in an area where nothing falls on you,'' she explained.
   Mary Oyervides said she, along with her husband and two
children, spent the last two nights in a car, then in a tent. Her
7-year-old daughter, she said, was with her the day of the quake
and witnessed flying bricks and trembling buildings. For a few days
after, she said, ``when something was not moving she would think it
was moving.''
   Now, she said, ``she just holds on to us.''
   Randy Graff, who works as a Red Cross volunteer at a Santa Cruz
shelter, said he also notices lingering fears. ``When there was an
aftershock (Thursday), I watched people get off their cots and
start running,'' he said. ``People are cracking under the
pressure.''
   But others are coping with their losses by getting involved.
Doctors and nurses have offered their services at the free
Watsonville clinic. Scores of volunteers have showed up to help the
Red Cross at shelters.
   One is Ken Biby, who lost his mobile home and many of his
belongings in the quake.
   ``I've been keeping myself busy,'' he said. ``As long as I'm
doing this, I ain't got all of that on my mind.''
   He said he and his family are planning to move next week to
Alaska. Originally, he had planned to wait until next summer, but
he said, ``This was the extra push I needed.''
   Biby is pragmatic about his plight.
   ``If I had lost a kid, I probably would have gone crazy,'' he
said. ``I face reality. Material things can be replaced. Humans
can't. I got my truck, I got my wife and my kids. That's enough.''
   And for those who are staying in Santa Cruz County, there's a
combination of resiliency and an acceptance of nature's quirks.
``You can take your choice,'' Miss Hervey said. ``There's stuff all
over the world that can scare your shorts off.''
   Red Cross volunteer Graff said he also is staying and expects
others will too. ``People here,'' he said, ``are trying to gather
their things, their thoughts, fix themselves up and dust themselves
off and be ready for the next one.''
</TEXT>
