<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Nuclear     10-21 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Nuclear,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Demonstrate in Soviet Kazakhstan Against Nuclear Testing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people rallied in Kazakhstan on
Saturday to protest nuclear testing in the Central Asian republic,
Tass reported.
   The Soviet news agency said protesters gathered in the capital
of the republic, Alma-Ata, to call for an end to testing in the
Semipalatinsk area of Kazakhstan and a halt to testing by the
United States in Nevada.
   Protesters in Semipalatinsk itself and other towns in Kazakhstan
also held protests, it said. Tass gave no specific figure for the
number of people at the rallies.
   Tass said the protests were organized by a Soviet anti-nuclear
group called ``Nevada-Semipalatinsk,'' the most prominent
grassroots anti-nuclear group in the Soviet Union.
   Infant mortality in the Semipalatinsk region is among the
highest in the country and the cancer rate there has been climbing
sharply for 15 years, a prominent Kazakhstan health official told
the crowd in the city of Alma Ata.
   The protesters appealed for the Soviet Union's legislature to
put the ``immediate closing of the Semipalatinsk'' testing site on
its agenda, Tass said.
   On Friday, about 150 students from Kazakhstan converged on the
Defense Ministry's General Staff building in Moscow to call for an
end to the underground tests in their homeland.
   A nuclear device was exploded Thursday with a yield of 20 to 75
kilotons, Tass reported.
</TEXT>
