<FIRST>r i AM-Sweden-Palme     10-21 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-Palme,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palme's Widow Criticizes Police, Press</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DICK SODERLUND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of Swedish prime minister
Olof Palme said Saturday that police and the press ``sabotaged''
the inquiry into her husband's murder and the subsequent trial.
   Lisbeth Palme was the chief witness against a local career
criminal, Christer Pettersson, whose July conviction in the slaying
was thrown out earlier this month by an appeals court, which cited
insufficient evidence.
   Mrs. Palme made her first direct public comment on Sweden's
``trial of the century'' in a 30-minute TV interview. She accused
the Swedish tabloids and other media of interfering in the inquiry,
buying information from sources, including police, and hounding her.
   Mrs. Palme also lambasted the police. She said she knew of
officers who accepted money for leaks, but she did not identify
them.
   Mrs. Palme herself has been criticized by the press for
hindering the investigation into her husband's death by setting
pre-conditions for her participation in police lineups and court
testimony.
   Her demand that any recording of her testimony be banned was
granted in court.
   In Saturday's TV interview, Mrs. Palme said she stuck to her
testimony that 43-year old Christer Pettersson was her husband's
murderer.
   Palme was killed Feb. 28, 1986, while he walked with his wife on
a Stockholm street.
   Mrs. Palme testified she saw Pettersson when she looked up from
her dying husband and was ``100 percent'' certain he was the gunman.
   Legal experts said that unequivocal statement would prohibit her
from testifying against anyone else accused of the crime.
</TEXT>
