<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-21 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frost in the South, Snow in the Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell in the Midwest on Saturday, flooding was expected in
parts of the Northeast, and frost warnings were posted in Florida.
   Record low temperatures were set for the second day in a row
from Miami to the Florida Panhandle as a cold snap continued to
chill the area. Clewiston was the Sunshine state's coldest spot
with a 29-degree reading.
   Warnings of frost and subfreezing temperatures were also posted
for areas of the Carolinas, with the temperature warnings extending
into southeast Tennessee, Georgia and Alabama.
   Scattered snow fell in the mountains of northern Georgia and
North Carolina. Two inches of snow was reported at Beach Mountain,
N.C., by early afternoon.
   Snow fell in Wisconsin, Michigan and Illinois and in parts of
Tennessee, Kentucky and West Virginia. Five inches was reported at
South Bend, Ind., 3 inches at Milwaukee, and an inch in Wausau, Wis.
   Rain and occasional thunderstorms extended from New York across
central New England. An inch and a half of rain fell in Milleville,
N.J., and Bridgeport, Conn.
   A flood warning was in effect in southeast New Jersey, where
heavy rain and high tide levels were reported. Coastal flooding was
possible as far north as Rhode Island.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 32
degrees at Kalamazoo, Mich., to 87 degrees at Yuma, Ariz.
