<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Uzbekistan     10-21 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Uzbekistan,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uzbekistan Parliament Replaces Premier, Passes Language Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The premier of Uzbekistan, who has been struggling
with growing ethnic nationalism and unrest, was replaced by a
younger Communist Party official, Tass reported Saturday.
   Uzbekistan's parliament also passed a compromise language law
that failed to satisfy Uzbek nationalists who have taken to the
streets several times in the past week to protest. Hundreds of
people were reported arrested.
   The parliament removed Premier Gairat Kadyrov at a two-day
session that ended Saturday and replaced him with 48-year-old
Mirakhmat Mirkasymov, a longtime Uzbek party official, Tass said.
   Kadyrov, 61, had been premier of the central Asian republic
since 1984. Tass said he would be transferred to a new post but did
not elaborate.
   Kadyrov had struggled in recent months swelling Uzbek
nationalism, which led to formation of a grass-roots political
movement and ethnic unrest that killed 100 people in the Fergana
Valley.
   The new language law fueled further unrest. Tass said the law
would make Uzbek the official langauge of the republic, correcting
the ``historical injustice'' dictator Josef Stalin committed in the
1930s by forcing Russian on the population.
   At the same time, Tass said, Russian and other languages common
in Uzbekistan, such as Tajik, could still be used by all groups for
``inter-ethnic communications.''
   A spokesman for the Uzbek Writers' Union said militia units
continued to patrol the republic's capital of Tashkent on Saturday
to prevent further demonstrations by the new grass-roots movement,
known as Berlik, or Unity.
   ``All the streets and squares are blocked by the police,'' said
the spokesman, who commented on condition of anonymity. ``There is
no traffic, but people keep gathering in groups with slogans
addressing their demands.''
   A similar law passed in the republic of Moldavia last summer
raised protests by ethnic Moldavians and prolonged strikes by
Russian speakers.
   In the Baltic and Caucasus regions as well as other areas of the
country, popular movements have openly held meetings and protests
and won the support of many top government officials.
   But in Tashkent, hundreds of people have been arrested since
Thursday during Berlik-sponsored protests, including the movement's
leader, Abdurakhim Pulatov, group sources said.
   Residents said they did not know if Mirkasymov had played a role
in the efforts to suppress the movement.
   He has held senior Communist Party jobs in the republic for the
past 16 years, Tass said.
   Kadyrov was reprimanded at a regional party congress in 1986 for
failing to ease the chronic unemployment in the republic of 20
million people. Such criticism has persisted.
   Last year, Pravda, the Communist Party newspaper, ridiculed
Kadyrov for his handling of a land and water dispute. The affair
climaxed when an angry crowd cornered Kadyrov, who had to radio
guards for help.
   In the Fergana Valley in June, Uzbek nationalists clashed with
minority Meskhetian Turks. Activists attributed much of the
violence to pent-up anger over economic conditions in the poor,
cotton-growing republic.
   Also Saturday, Tass said the Uzbek parliament passed a law
banning ethnic restrictions on the right to vote.
   A recent law championed by Estonion nationalists in their Baltic
republic set residency requirements for voting and touched off
strikes by Russians and other ethnic groups.
</TEXT>
