<FIRST>u a AM-Quake-BayBridge 1stLd-Writethru a0626 10-21 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quake-Bay Bridge, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0626,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bridge Part To Be Sawed In Half</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 1-2 to CORRECT spelling of `blowtorches' and first
name of spokesman to Greg, sted Grey.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers used concrete saws and blowtorches
Saturday to cut through a collapsed section of the San
Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge, operating under a tight deadline to
reopen a major link knocked out by Tuesday's earthquake.
   The California Department of Transportation had hoped to remove
the collapsed section of roadway on Saturday, but that was likely
delayed until Monday by the decision to saw the 250-ton piece in
half, said Greg Bayol of the Transportation Department.
   The Transportation Department has set a four-week deadline and a
$1 million pricetag for reopening the 8.5-mile bridge, which
carries 270,000 cars each day. But some officials have said the
repairs could take two months.
   Bayol said officials decided overnight Saturday to avoid
unnecessarily adding stress to the tower supporting the roadway
piece, which is 50 feet long, 60 feet wide and holds five lanes of
traffic.
   ``They were afraid if they lifted 250 tons the shifting of
weight would be more of a problem than if they cut it,'' he said.
``It would be more safe for everyone concerned if they cut the slab
into two sections and lifted it out one at a time.''
   The pieces will be lowered by a 190-foot barge-based crane onto
a waiting barge. The section is to be repaired and reassembled at
nearby Alameda, Bayol said.
   The cutting should not delay the reopening, because other repair
work can continue during the weekend, he said.
   A section of the upper span of the bridge shook loose during
Tuesday's earthquake and crashed down on the lower roadway,
destroying several vehicles and killing a 23-year-old Berkeley
woman whose car sped over the edge moments after the gap opened.
Television pictures of the pitched upper section provided the first
graphic indication of the strength of the quake.
   Workers are using diamond-tipped saws to cut an 18-inch-wide
strip through the concrete roadway, and blowtorches to cut through
the steel frame, said Jim Drago of the Transportation Department.
   Repair and reopening of the bridge is being closely watched in
the Bay Area because the span is vital to commuters. For now,
residents will have to rely on jampacked Bay Area Rapid Transit
systems and a makeshift fleet of donated ferry boats.
   Officials are still unclear why only the one section of the
bridge failed, Bayol said.
   Theories center on the notion that the collapsed section was at
the point where the different construction techniques used to build
the 1930s-era bridge are joined, Bayol said. Jutting west out of
Oakland the bridge is supported underneath only by towers, while
the central cantilevered section is held up by steel girders from
above as well as towers.
   ``This one section is unique to the whole bridge,'' Bayol said.
``It was more rigid. Maybe it didn't move as much.''
   Jim Roberts, chief of structures for the state transportation
department, said the damaged section appears to be in good shape.
If it can be salvaged, it will be put back in place as soon as
possible, he said.
   The bottom section of the two-tiered bridge suffered three
puncture holes, opening portions of the roadway to the water below,
Bayol said. Transportation Department officials have given
conflicting accounts of whether that section can be repaired, or
whether it will have to be replaced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
