<SECOND>AM-BRF--Abortion Protest,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Demonstrators Chain Themselves to Women's Clinic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEVITTOWN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 anti-abortion demonstrators
were arrested Saturday after they chained shut the doors of a
clinic and shackled themselves together, police said.
   The 101 protesters, members of the Bi-state Operation Rescue
Network, were charged with disorderly conduct, resisting arrest and
obstructing justice after their arrests at the Long Island
Gynecological Clinic, said Nassau County police spokesman, Charles
Koller.
   About 250 protesters were in place by 7 a.m., two hours before
the clinic opened, said organization spokeswoman Esther Lerach.
   Fourteen women scheduled for treatment were kept from entering,
said the clinic's manager, Lois Colasuonno.
   Police carted off some of the protestors on stretchers; others
had linked themselves together with thick metal chains that were
also attached to the building's front and rear doors. Police used
electric saws to cut the chains, Koller said.
