<FIRST>r a AM-ShuttleCanister     10-21 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle Canister,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Payload Canister Damaged</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A canister used to move space
shuttle payloads was damaged Saturday when a crane apparently
failed and dropped a 20-ton concrete weight on it, NASA reported.
   The weight struck the top of the 65-foot-tall carrier ``striking
a door a glancing blow as it fell to the floor of the canister,'' a
statement said.
   The concrete weight being lifted out of the canister ``was just
about clear of the canister's doors when an apparent crane failure
caused the weight to fall,'' it said.
   The concrete was being used to simulate a payload for a test.
The canister is the size of a shuttle cargo bay.
   The statement said there were no injuries and an inspection was
being made to determine the extent of the damage. An investigation
of the accident was begun.
   The container is one of two available at the Kennedy Space
Center for transporting satellites and other shuttle payloads from
a processing building to the launch pad. NASA said the accident
would have no impact on launch schedules.
   The damaged canister was recently used to check out Launch Pad
39A, which has undergone renovation and is to be used for a shuttle
liftoff in December for the first time in nearly four years.
   The canister and its enclosed piece of concrete had recently
been moved from the pad to an assembly building, where the accident
took place.
</TEXT>
