<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 1855EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Highway     10-21 0742</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Highway,0769</SECOND>
<HEAD>Critics Say California's Vow to Fix Roads Is Politics, Not Planning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Earthquake experts contended Saturday
the state's rush to strengthen elevated roadways like the Oakland
stretch that crushed scores of motorists smacks more of politics
than much-needed safety planning.
   The sudden activity demonstrates again that state government
often reacts to the most visible results of the last quake, while
ignoring warnings of what is likely to happen in future temblors,
some state experts said.
   ``There are too few people in power _ political visionaries _
who have a strong will to lead us to better prepare for future
quakes,'' said Richard Eisner, who heads the state-funded Bay Area
Earthquake Preparedness Project.
   ``Of course, we have to look back, but we must begin to look
forward too'' and devote more resources to preparing for
earthquakes, he said.
   But other observers asserted Californians would never pay the
billions of dollars needed to prepare for all quake scenarios.
Given resources limited by tax-cutting Proposition 13 as well as
pressing needs elsewhere, the most sensible alternative is to act
on lessons learned in past quakes.
   ``You're always short of money for those freeways and other
things,'' said former Gov. Pat Brown. ``Earthquakes are so seldom,
you know, and you probably think things should be done but they're
a low priority.''
   He said it was unfair to fault government for simply fixing
problems revealed in past quakes, given lack of money to do more.
   ``We learn more every time there's an earthquake, and we act on
it. That's what we should be doing,'' added Caltrans Chief Engineer
Bill Schaefer.
   But Ed Hensley, a top official with the state Seismic Safety
Commission, said the swift move to speed improvements of Oakland's
Interstate 880 only after it claimed so many lives appears to be a
political reaction.
   The highway's apparent flaws were just some of many earthquake
hazards long noted in dusty government reports, he said.
   Hensley said a lengthy 1982 state study on effects of a big
quake in the Bay Area noted what some consulting engineers suspect
contributed to I-880's collapse _ extremely unstable ground beneath
the highway.
   The study predicted the former marsh would liquefy in a big
quake. ``So far as I know, nobody at the top paid attention to that
study,'' nor to his own Seismic Safety Commission research on
likely future earthquake effects, Hensley said.
   ``These documents seem to be taken as interesting academic
exercises until something happens,'' Hensley said.
   Jim Roberts, a top structural engineer for the California
Transportation Department, said Friday that Gov. George Deukmejian
``obviously is going to speed up'' research to find ways to
quake-proof the 1\ miles of I-880 that collapsed, killing scores of
motorists.
   The 1950s-era double-decker freeway is among four such
structures in the Bay Area. Another, the Embarcadero Freeway in San
Francisco, was severely damaged in Tuesday's quake and shut down
for lengthy repair. The two others, a portion of I-280 and the
Central Viaduct, received less damage.
   Roberts confirmed that the four structures' earthquake
stability, particularly their aged double-support columns, have
worried engineers for years. He admitted that warnings came even
from within his own department, including a May 31 memorandum that
mentioned the need to act soon to bolster some multi-column bridges.
   The transportation department, however, has put off column work
on the freeways pending more study. Instead, it is readying a $55
million effort to strengthen ``single-column'' freeways as a result
of the 1971 San Fernando Valley earthquake, which severely damaged
such roads, Roberts said.
   He also acknowledged the department hadn't asked for research
money to seek technology to strengthen freeways like I-880 until
after the 1987 Whittier quake, when more flaws were revealed in
multi-columned structures.
   Now the department will seek $200 million to $300 million to
strengthen the structures once research is finished, he said.
   Since the 1971 quake, the department has completed ``first
phase'' work on 1,300 bridges, including double-columned bridge
entryways like I-880, to bolster horizontal decking. Ironically,
installation of strengthening cables may have contributed to
1-880's collapse by pulling down sections of the roadway jarred
loose by the quake, said Dr. Pyotr Moncarz, a Palo Alto engineer.
   ``You can talk to 100 engineers and get 100 different answers''
as to why the section collapsed, retorted Caltrans' Schaefer, who
added that the department will spare no effort to learn causes of
the bridge failure.
</TEXT>
