<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-USGS     10-21 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-USGS,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>2,000 Aftershocks and More Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 2,000 aftershocks have been
recorded since the big earthquake Oct. 17, government seismologists
said Saturday as they warned of the risk of further damage.
   The aftershocks are expected to last for several more days, with
some strong enough to cause additional harm, especially to
structures weakened in the original 6.9 quake, according to the
U.S. Geological Survey.
   An aftershock measuring 4.6 rattled the quake area anew Saturday
afternoon. The USGS said it was centered about 8 miles northeast of
Santa Cruz, just a few miles from the epicenter of the big quake.
   Although the aftershocks are generally decreasing in magnitude,
there is still a small chance of a strong temblor measuring 5.0 or
more on the Richter scale of ground movement in the next few days,
said USGS seismologist William Bakun.
   The 6.9 quake relieved strain on the San Andreas fault in the
southern Santa Cruz Mountains, greatly reducing the chances of an
equally powerful quake in the same spot over the next 50 years,
said geologist Bill Ellsworth.
   But the quake did nothing to reduce the chances of another big
temblor along a 25-mile stretch of the San Andreas north of the
Oct. 17 rupture, or along any of the other faults in California,
Ellsworth said.
   ``There are a number of small segments within the Bay area that
are estimated to have a reasonably high chance of rupturing in a
magnitude 7 earthquake during the next 30 years,'' Ellsworth said.
   Three segments, two along the Hayward fault on the east side of
San Francisco Bay and one along the San Andreas, each have about a
20 percent chance of breaking in the 30-year period, he said.
   ``There are many other faults in the Bay area, most of which we
do not have the same kinds of geological information to build these
kinds of forecasts,'' Ellsworth said. ``So in some sense the
long-term forecasts for the Bay region, the chance of another
magnitude 7 earthquake in the next 30 years, is probably an
understatement of the probability.''
   As of Saturday, 17 aftershocks of magnitude 4.0 or larger and 71
measuring at least 3.0 had been recorded, the USGS said. The
largest was the 5.2 temblor that occurred 37 minutes after the main
shock Tuesday evening. The second largest was a 5.0 that occurred
at 3:14 a.m. Thursday.
   ``Because of this continuing hazard, we are urging that
earthquake preparedness measures continue to be taken, and that
extreme caution be exercised in and around damaged structures,''
said USGS geologist Thomas Holzer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
