<SECOND>AM-Israel-Murders, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0543,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Suspected In Stranglings, Overnight Policy Reconsidered</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with report that suspect was informant,
more victims likely; pickup graf 9 pvs, `Police Commissioner...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police searched on Saturday for a Palestinian
suspected of strangling seven people in Tel Aviv, and the case has
prompted officials to review the policy that lets workers from the
occupied lands stay overnight in the city.
   Police said the murders apparently stemmed from financial
disputes between the suspect and his victims over drugs and
prostitution, but they would not rule out a political motive.
   Army radio quoted police officials as saying the suspect was
known as a criminal and was given an overnight permit because he
served as an informant for Israel's security forces. Tel Aviv
police declined comment.
   The victims included prostitutes and drug dealers. Some were
Jews and others were Arabs, including some from the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The investigation began Friday when residents of an impoverished
Tel Aviv neighborhood reported bad odors coming from an apartment.
   Police arrived to discover the decomposing bodies of two women
and one man hidden under mattresses in the apartment.
   They said the investigation led them to the Arab-Jewish Tel Aviv
suburb of Jaffa, where the bodies of three women and one man were
found.
   News reports said police suspected more bodies may be found in
southern Tel Aviv.
   Assistant Inspector General Yigal Markus, the Tel Aviv police
chief, said the main suspect was a Palestinian from the occupied
territories who had a permit to stay in Tel Aviv at night.
   Israel army radio said the victims apparently were strangled
with nylon string.
   Police Commissioner David Krauss said Saturday the policy of
granting permits to Palestinian workers to spend the night in Tel
Aviv will be re-examined.
   ``Tel Aviv should not serve as a haven for criminals from the
(occupied) territories,'' he said.
   Thousands of Palestinian workers travel each morning to Tel Aviv
but need a special permit to stay the night. Many hide in
apartments, warehouses or shelters to avoid the journey back home
or the possibility of being caught in a Palestinian commercial
strike.
   Police officials have said they are instructed not to arrest
laborers staying in Tel Aviv illegally. However, measures have been
taken to limit the flow into Israel of suspected criminals and
activists of the 22-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israeli
rule of the territories.
   In June, the army began requiring that Palestinian workers from
the Gaza Strip present magnetic ID cards to enter Israel. Leaders
of the uprising have ordered strikes and attacks to protest the
step, but they appear to have lost the battle.
   In July, police gave the army a list of about 3,300 Palestinians
it wanted permanently barred from entering Israel because of
suspected criminal activity.
</TEXT>
