<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-NBC     10-21 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-NBC,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC News Head Angered at Networks' Slow Start on Quake Coverage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``failsafe'' in 13th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of NBC News has criticized the
network's initial response to San Francisco's earthquake and
ordered executives to find out why NBC was late with its coverage.
   An internal memo issued Friday by NBC News President Michael
Gartner and made available by a source was written after the
network received complaints from affiliates.
   Although the network eventually broadcast non-stop coverage of
Tuesday's quake, it lagged far behind its rivals both in reports
and pictures.
   NBC's first live pictures from the scene didn't air until 9:08
p.m. EDT Tuesday, well after ABC, CBS and CNN were broadcasting
live shots.
   Gartner's memo blamed some of the delay in coverage on
``problems and confusion'' that were not related to technical
problems. NBC spokewoman Peggy Hubble confirmed Saturday that the
memo was by Gartner.
   Gartner had said in an interview Wednesday that the delay was
because NBC's San Francisco affiliate, KRON-TV, had been harder hit
by the earthquake than other network affiliates, and was knocked
off the air longer.
   However, Francis Martin, president of Chronicle Broadcasting,
which owns KRON, said in a letter Friday that the station was back
on the air by 8:35 p.m, 31 minutes after the earthquake.
   In a letter to James R. Sefert, chairman of NBC's affiliate
board, Martin said NBC could have had a satellite feed of pictures
from the scene then had it asked. It also could have gotten
pictures shortly after that via a KRON hookup with station KCRA-TV
in Sacramento, or from NBC-owned KNBC-TV in Burbank, Calif., Martin
wrote.
   By 8:50 p.m. EDT, Martin said, there were three ways NBC could
have picked up KRON's signal. Had it done so then, he said, that
would have made NBC ``second to ABC in terms of initial coverage
and would have made CBS third.''
   Gartner's memo began by praising news employees' hard work in
covering the quake, said an executive who requested anonymity. Then
it changed tone.
   ``Let me express my dismay and anger over our not being on the
air right away Tuesday night,'' Gartner wrote.
   ``We had problems and confusion that were not related to the
technical problems of getting material from our affiliate,'' he
said. ``This is just unacceptable. Period.''
   ``I don't think we have a workable procedure for dealing with
crises like this,'' the memo said, adding that there will be one
soon.
   He said he had asked a top NBC News executive to investigate
what happened and then ``quickly develop a failsafe procedure to
ensure that we're never again late in getting on the air.''
</TEXT>
