<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Military     10-21 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Military,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Soldiers Start Group to Fight Military Corruption</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 Soviet soldiers and seamen formed an
unsanctioned organization Saturday to fight military corruption and
ensure that ``the army is not used against the people,'' a group
spokeman said.
   The founding congress of Shchit, Russian for ``shield,'' went
ahead despite heavy opposition from military officials, spokesman
Dmitri Chechell said.
   He said the group wants to help soldiers and sailors battle
corruption in the armed forces and make sure the military is not
used as it was at Tbilisi in April, when soldiers charged
pro-independence protesters. Twenty people died in the unrest in
the city, the capital of Georgia.
   Chechell said many of the delegates to the congress left their
military units illegally to attend Saturday's meeting. He said some
were even placed under house arrest to prevent them from coming.
   Soviet Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov, KGB chairman Vladimir
A. Kryuchkov and other top officials were invited but failed to
appear, Chechell said.
   However, Communist Party gadfly Boris N. Yeltsin and other
progressive Soviet lawmakers did attend, he said.
   Shchit will fight ``arbitrariness, nepotism, corruption and
cover-ups,'' Chechell said.
   The group is calling for fewer top-ranking officers and limits
on dishonorable discharges, which are often used as ``revenge
against inconveniently honorable people,'' he said.
   He said organizers expect to encounter major opposition from
authorities when they try to officially register the new group as
an organization.
   The congress was scheduled to continue through Sunday.
</TEXT>
