<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Abortion 2ndLd-Writethru a0642 10-21 0894</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Abortion, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0642,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Vetoes Abortion Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with reaction. Moves up grafs
13-14 pvs, ``Congressional action.'' Picks up 15th graf pvs, ``Supporters
of''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Saturday kept his pledge to
veto legislation that would liberalize abortion law by making
federal funds available for poor women in cases of incest and rape.
   Bush said he was unwilling to expend tax dollars unless the
mother's life is endangered, which is the only way Medicaid can
fund abortions under current law.
   ``This year, regrettably, the Congress has expanded the
circumstances in which federal appropriated funds could be used to
pay for abortions,'' Bush said in a veto message released by the
White House.
   The Senate on Thursday completed action on the abortion
language, passing on a 67-31 vote a $156.7 billion fiscal 1990
spending bill for the departments of Health and Human Services,
Labor and Education that included the expanded abortion funding
provision despite Bush's threat of a veto.
   The House passed the measure the previous week by a much more
narrow margin, 216-206 _ far short of the two-thirds vote that
would be needed to override a veto.
   However, House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., has indicated
he would make an override attempt. Foley and other Democrats say
they do not believe there will be sufficient votes.
   The leading sponsor of the abortion language change, Rep.
Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., has said supporters will attempt to attach
the language to other legislation.
   Congressional action to broaden the federal guidelines that have
covered abortions for Medicaid mothers since 1981 came amid
increased activism nationwide by pro-choice forces angered by the
Supreme Court's decision in July to allow state discretion on
abortion law.
   Pro-choice advocates had been buoyed by congressional passage of
the new abortion language and by the failure of Florida Gov. Bob
Martinez to get bills toughening that state's abortion laws through
a special session of the Florida legislature earlier this month.
   They expressed dismay Saturday over Bush's decision.
   ``With one stroke of his pen, President Bush today condemned
impoverished women to continue crisis pregnancies that can destroy
their lives,'' said Kate Michelman, executive director of the
National Abortion Rights Action League, the political arm of the
pro-choice movement. She said Bush ``defied public opinion and
pandered to extremists.''
   But Douglas Johnson, legislative director of the pro-life
National Right to Life Committee, said ``Pesident Bush has acted to
protect innocent human life. Now pro-life Americans must persuade
the House of Representatives to back him up.''
   In his veto message, Bush said ``I have informed the Congress on
numerous occasions that I would veto legislation if it permitted
the use of appropriated funds to pay for abortions other than those
in which the life of the mother would be endangered if the fetus
were carried to term.''
   He noted that he wrote to the Senate on Tuesday warning he would
veto such language.
   In his brief veto message, Bush said he also was unhappy that
the spending bill did not provide adequate funding for the Pell
grant program for higher education, and that it ``failed to provide
needed flexibility in the use of HHS discretionary funds to combat
HIV AIDs, one of America's highest public health priorities.''
   Bush had indicated last week he was willing to discuss
compromise language on abortion, but then made what some saw as a
concession to conservative Republicans.
   Supporters of the expanded guidelines said the president's
position discriminated unfairly against poor mothers. Bush supports
the practice of abortion in cases of rape or incest, as well as
when the mother's life is endangered, but he does not favor using
federal funds for the first two situations.
   He said in a news conference Oct. 13 that he was ``not looking
for any conflict over this'' and was interested in seeing if
conference language could be worked out by the House and Senate
that ``may be able to avoid a veto on my part.''
   Bush said when he wrote to the Senate last Tuesday that he had
not reached his position on abortion ``easily or lightly.''
   ``Since 1981, the federal government has determined, I think
wisely, that taxpayer funds should be used for abortion in only the
most narrow of circumstances: where the life of the mother is
endangered. If abortion funding were expanded to include other
circumstances, it would be difficult to limit to the few cases of
actual rape or incest, and could have the unintended consequence of
allowing the taking of countless other lives of unborn children
well beyond the few cased argued as reasons for the proposed
legislative change.''
   That letter came on the heels of what abortion proponents had
seen as a glimmer of hope for a shift in Bush's position. In his
Oct. 13 news conference he had said he wanted to ``see if there's
room for flexibility'' on the question in Congress.
   His veto means the entire $156.7 billion spending package goes
back to Congress.
   It is the third bill Bush has vetoed since he took office. In
June he vetoed legislation raising the minimum wage to $4.55 an
hour, and in July he vetoed a measure placing restrictions on a $6
billion program for the United States to build a new jet fighter,
the FSX, with Japan.
</TEXT>
