<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 2000EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Vetoes     10-21 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Vetoes,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Now Has Vetoed Three Bills Since Taking Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Abortion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's veto Saturday of legislation
allowing federally financed abortions for rape and incest victims
marks the third time since he took office that he has exercised
that constitutional prerogative.
   Bush said he vetoed the $156.7 billion health, education and
labor spending measure that included the abortion provision because
he opposed expanding the use of tax dollars for abortion.
   Current law makes federal Medicaid funds for abortion available
to poor women only when the mother's life is endangered.
   This summer the president vetoed a bill that effectively would
have killed a joint production agreement between the United States
and Japan for the FSX jet fighter.
   In June he also vetoed legislation that would have raised the
minimum wage to $4.55 an hour by October 1991.
   Congressional opponents of the fighter deal wanted to place
restrictions on the transfer of certain advanced U.S. technology to
the Japanese in the development of the $6 billion aircraft by
General Dynamics and Mitsubishi Heavy Industries.
   Bush argued the restrictions were an infringement on
presidential powers to conduct foreign policy. The Senate last
month failed by a single vote to override the veto.
   Bush's first veto came after less than six months in office when
Congress approved an increase of the hourly minimum wage from $3.55
to $4.55. Bush had offered an increase to $4.25 an hour over a
longer period, with a six-month subminimum $3.40 an hour ``training
wage'' for new employees.
   Democrats initially resisted the subminimum wage but later
included a provision allowing the lower wage for first-time
employees with fewer than 60 days' work experience in the measure
Bush rejected.
   Neither the House nor Senate could muster the votes needed to
override that veto.
   Last week the Democratic-controlled House Labor and Education
Committee approved a new minimum wage bill with Bush's $4.25
ceiling, but the panel insisted the increase must come in two
45-cent increments by October 1991. It also retained the 60-day
limit on the lower wage.
   Senate sources have said the modified House bill could be
brought up within the next three weeks.
</TEXT>
