<FIRST>u a AM-SF-Quake-Glance 1stLd-Writethru a0575 10-21 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF-Quake-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0575,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summary of Quake-related Developments</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf under `casualties' to UPDATE with rescue of survivor.
SUBS 2nd graf under `The quake and its aftershocks' to UPDATE with more
than 2,000 aftershocks, another registering over 4.0.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Summary of developments related to the California earthquake:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DAMAGE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The earthquake may turn out to be the most expensive natural
disaster in U.S. history, with state officials putting the current
estimate at $5.5 billion. The 1906 earthquake and fire in San
Francisco cost as much as $5.8 billion in current dollars,
according to the Independent Insurance Agents of America.
   The American Red Cross says at least 729 homes and residential
buildings were destroyed and 4,950 others damaged along 75 miles of
the San Andreas Fault. The state Office of Emergency Services said
6,568 people remained displaced Saturday, 4,500 in Santa Cruz
County.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CASUALTIES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Stunned rescuers pulled a 57-year-old longshoreman alive from
the debris of I-880 Saturday, long after most had given up hope of
finding survivors. Buck Helm, the first person rescued alive since
Tuesday night, was rushed to a local hospital suffering a serious
chest injury but doctors said he was not in imminent danger.
   Fifty-five deaths have been confirmed, with the toll expected to
grow as more bodies are pulled out of the wreckage where I-880
collapsed. Officials said 34 bodies had been pulled from the I-880
rubble by Saturday, with dozens of missing people expected to be
counted among the victims; elsewhere in Northern California, at
least 21 people have been killed.
   The state OES reports that 3,011 people were injured in eight
counties of Northern California. Thirty Red Cross shelters were
housing up to 5,000 people Saturday.
 
</TEXT>
<NOTE>THE QUAKE AND AFTERSHOCKS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The earthquake hit at 5:04 p.m. Tuesday, registered 6.9 on the
Richter scale, and was centered on the San Andreas Fault 14 miles
northeast of Santa Cruz and 57 miles south of San Francisco n the
Santa Cruz Mountains. Scientists pinpointed the epicenter in the
northeast corner of the Nisene Marks State Park, near the top of
Aptos Creek.
   More than 2,000 aftershocks have been recorded, including one of
5.2 that came 40 minutes after the initial quake. Fourteen
aftershocks have registered at least 4.0, considered capable of
causing moderate damage. Seismologists say aftershocks will be felt
for several months.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FEDERAL ASSISTANCE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush toured the devastated area Friday. He has signed
a disaster relief declaration for seven Bay area counties and
authorized an initial $273 million. House Speaker Tom Foley said
the House would vote to provide the estimated $2.5 billion needed
in federal aid in a stopgap money bill that comes up on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WORLD SERIES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Baseball Commissioner Fay Vincent said the World Series between
the Oakland Athletics and San Francisco Giants is tentatively
scheduled to resume Tuesday at Candlestick Park, pending final
approval by Mayor Art Agnos this weekend. Times for Game 3 and
other remaining games have not been announced.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HIGHWAY CLOSURES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge closed for several weeks after
one section collapsed. Nimitz Freeway (I-880) from the Bay Bridge
south to downtown Oakland. Embarcadero Freeway (I-480) in San
Francisco closed until June because of severe cracking but will not
be torn down. Highway 101 northbound at Highway 92 overpass.
Highway 17 in Santa Cruz Mountains from Scotts Valley to Highway 9
for an estimated three weeks due to slides. Highway 25 from Highway
101 to 15 miles south of Hollister in San Benito County due to
slides.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>QUAKE HOTLINE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The San Francisco Earthquake and Relief Assistance Hotline,
1-900-500-HELP, was established Friday. It offers callers news
updates, American Red Cross information such as shelter locations
and blood banks, status of transportation and utility systems,
state and federal government information and survival tips.
   The 24-hour service, operated by Starbridge Communications Co.
of Los Angeles in conjunction with AT&amp;T, will be updated daily by
celebrities and sports stars such as former Los Angeles Dodgers
catcher Steve Yeager and can handle 28,000 calls a minute. Each
call costs $5, with net proceeds donated to the Red Cross for its
earthquake relief effort.
   The Red Cross says a number will be set up next week for
inquiries about quake victims but the information is not being
given out now.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WEATHER</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Rain throughout the region Saturday hampered recovery efforts
and was forecast to continue through the weekend. Most affected was
Santa Cruz County, where landslides caused by the quake destroyed
or damaged scores of houses and thousands of people were sleeping
outside.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
