<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 1941EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Quake     10-21 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Quake,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Out in Cold After Chinese Quake</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of people left homeless by the
worst earthquake in northern China in more than a decade spent a
third night outdoors Saturday, and the government delivered
truckloads of food to devastated towns.
   ``The nighttime is unbearably cold,'' said Guan Xiaoping, a
peasant from Guiren Village. Like almost every person in the
village of 2,400, he lost his home in a series of severe tremors
Wednesday night and Thursday morning.
   Guiren was one of 40 villages, mostly in Shanxi province, that
were severely damaged by the quakes. They killed at least 29
people, injured more than 150, destroyed an estimated 27,500 homes
and left more than 50,000 homeless.
   Guan told a Western reporter he had received noodles, bread,
clothing and millet from the government. He also said soldiers had
helped him build a temporary wood-and-mud shelter.
   But he said there had been no promises of help in rebuilding his
home. ``For winter we will build stronger tents. We have no
choice,'' he said.
   The national television news, in its first extensive reporting
on the disaster, Saturday night showed truckloads of food being
delivered. It said local officials and the People's Liberation Army
were involved in relief operations.
   People wearing many layers of clothing to ward off the cold and
wind warmed themselves around fires and slept in hastily built
shelters of straw and bamboo.
   At least one aftershock strong enough to be felt jolted the area
Saturday morning. Beijing Radio, in a broadcast monitored in Tokyo,
said Saturday there have been about 1,500 aftershocks, four between
5.0 and 6.0 on the Richter scale.
   The biggest quakes late Wednesday and early Thursday measured
5.7 and 6.1 on the Richter scale, which measures ground motion. A
quake measuring 6.0 can cause severe damage in a populated area.
   The Communist Party's People's Daily said Saturday that 40
villages in a 320-square-mile area were damaged. The epicenter of
one quake was 135 miles west of Beijing.
   The newspaper said 1,600 soldiers had been mobilized to help in
relief operations and that such items as bread, noodles,
chopsticks, quilts, tents, mats and medical supplies had been
rushed to the affected areas.
   Chinese seismologists said the quakes were the worst to hit
northern China since 1976. That year, a quake measuring at least
7.8 on the Richter scale killed 240,000 people in the northeastern
city of Tangshan.
</TEXT>
