<DOCNO> AP891021-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 2013EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-ToughSurvivor 1stLd-Writethru a0644 10-21 0923</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Tough Survivor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0644,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf to add that Helm was teacher; inserts 2 new grafs
after 19th pvs, ``He has a ...,'' to add quotes; deletes grafs 24, 25 and
27 to tighten and adds new last graf with nickname. Note quote in 3rd graf.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quake Survivor: `We're Going to Call Him Lucky Bucky'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE CARPENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buck Alvin Helm, a beefy longshoreman who
splits his time between the Oakland waterfront and the Klamath
Mountains, is ``strong, tough and ornery.'' Those traits served him
well in a death-defying, 90-hour ordeal on a crumpled highway.
   Helm's family and friends know him as an occasionally
cantankerous, family-loving man with a booming voice who knows how
to survive. And survive he did through three nights of terrifying
conditions inside his crushed car in the concrete wreckage of the
Nimitz Freeway.
   Asked what kept his father alive so long, Greg Helm responded:
``He's an ornery old fart.''
   Helm, 57, has worked in the bay area since 1969 as a shipping
clerk for Local 34 of the International Longshoremen's and
Warehousemen's Union. A former teacher, he has worked most recently
at the Port of Oakland, keeping track of the cargo received and
delivered on the waterfront.
   Most weekends and sometimes on weekdays, he drives 250 miles
north to Weaverville on the edge of the Klamath Mountains to visit
his children and his ex-wife, with whom he remains good friends.
His silver Chevrolet Sprint, mashed in the wreckage, had nearly
200,000 miles on it.
   News of his miraculous survival and rescue shot through the town
of 3,500 like a lightning bolt Saturday.
   One woman came into Top's Market where Buck shops, the largest
grocery store in town, and hollered at the top of her lungs, ``They
found him! They found him!'', according to assistant manager Tony
Giassullo.
   A group of Helm's friends and relatives was watching television
together at the home of his ex-wife, Lorene, when news came that he
was alive.
   ``Everyone was happy, yelling, crying and holding each other,''
said Frank Desmond, a friend of Helm's son Jeff. ``Mrs. Helm was
saying, `Thank God!'''
   Said former next-to-door neighbor Cathy Hardisty: ``I still got
chills all over my body at him living through that.''
   Helm's tale of survival starts with his own misfortune in timing.
   After finishing up work at 5 p.m., Helm and Basil Parker, a
co-worker for the last six years, left the Howard Terminal and
headed north on the Nimitz, Parker for his home in Berkeley and
Helm for Weaverville. Seconds after passing Helm and waving to him,
Parker looked in his rear-view mirror as the earthquake struck;
Helm, who had been about 10 car lengths behind him, was gone.
   ``Right now, all I can say is I'm glad to see him alive,'' said
Parker. ``I'm happy for his family more than anything.''
   Helm, described by one acquaintance as about 6 feet tall, 240
pounds and ``pretty good-sized around the middle,'' is a well-known
figure in Weaverville. His family has lived there about 10 years _
sons Greg, by a first marriage, and Jeff, a high school student,
and fifth-grader Desiree.
   ``He was a real family man,'' said Bridgitte Calkins. ``We saw
him when he went to the football games and the soccer games with
his children. He's real friendly and real talkative.''
   Waitress Lory Hartland, 25, serves him cherry pie and coffee
almost every weekend at the Nugget Restaurant.
   ``He's big, strong, tough and ornery,'' she said. ``I'm not
surprised he survived. He always comes in here with all his kids
and their friends. He's a real good dad. I'm ecstatic he's alive.''
   So is Weaverville resident Fred Meyer, who described his friend
as ``a big bear of a guy.''
   ``He has a booming voice and a heart of gold,'' Meyer said.
   
   Peggy McConnell of Weaverville said Helm is one of her best
friends. She said he ``stands out as an individualist in this
fundamentalist, redneck little town.''
   McConnell, 40, described Helm's car as dirty and disorganized
and said it might have contained food and water. She said he had
access to a van that he slept in while in the Bay area in order to
save money, ``even though he makes plenty of money.''
   
   The day after the 6.9 quake, Helm's former wife walked into
Weaverville Variety Office Supply in a daze and spoke with store
owner Pat Zugg.
   ``She said she had a gut feeling that he was trapped in that
freeway,'' she said. ``She was pretty stunned. He hadn't called to
say he was OK, so she knew something wasn't right. He was very
family-oriented. Every time I saw him he was with his kids.''
   Helm's co-workers on the waterfront had known for days that he
was almost surely among the victims on the devastated stretch of
freeway. When radio and television reported he had been found, many
called in to the Local 34 office to share the good news.
   ``We're all ecstatic,'' said Dave Comport, a shipping
superintendent who works in the same terminal as Helm. ``We figured
that if anybody could make it, Buck Helm could. He's tough. He's a
fighter.''
   Frances Lona, secretary for the Local 34 main office in San
Francisco, characterized Helm and his co-workers as ``wild
characters,'' but said he is a great guy.
   He's now a guy with a new nickname, according to co-worker Bob
Bombarde.
   ``We're going to call him Lucky Bucky from now on,'' Bombarde
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
