<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 2019EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Transit     10-21 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Transit,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stay Off Roads Monday, Officials Plead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local transit officials are pleading with
commuters to stay off the roads Monday, the first business day for
tens of thousands since the quake damaged the Bay Bridge.
   In a plan put together by area transportation agencies,
commuters were asked to instead make use of subways, trains, buses
or ferries.
   The plan was hastily thrown together in an effort to avoid what
promises to be the worst traffic mess ever experienced here as
55,000 people who usually drive over the San Francisco-Oakland Bay
Bridge try other routes. An additional 10,000 people who normally
commute by bus will also need to find other routes.
   ``We have a very critical situation,'' Birch Buchtold, district
director for the state Department of Transportation, said Saturday.
   The 8-mile-long Bay Bridge, which lost a 50-foot section of its
top deck in Tuesday's earthquake, is a key link between San
Francisco and Oakland.
   But the transit problems are not limited to the bridge. The
Embarcadero Freeway in San Francisco is closed because of
structural failure and the Interstate 280 extension from downtown
to Highway 101 near Candlestick Park is also down for several
months.
   In Oakland, the Cypress section of Interstate 880, used by
160,000 cars daily, has been closed after a section collapsed,
killing dozens.
   State Highway 17, a vital link for 20,000 people who commute to
work in the Silicon Valley, is closed in Santa Cruz because of
landslides connected to Tuesday's 6.9-magnitude temblor.
</TEXT>
