Ford. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Harold Ford, D-Tenn., paid a $50 fine to
release his wife from jail in the District of Columbia on Saturday
after she was arrested for driving with an expired license, police
officials said.
   Dorothy Ford was stopped after she allegedly ran a red light
near the Capitol building Saturday morning, police said.
   When an officer discovered her driver's license had expired more
than a year ago, Mrs. Ford was arrested and taken to a nearby
police station, where she called her husband, police said.
   A police official said anyone caught driving with a license more
than 90 days out of date is subject to the $50 fine, which must be
paid when the infraction is discovered.
   She still faces a $75 fine for allegedly running the traffic
signal.
   The seven-term congressman was himself indicted two years ago in
connection with loans allegedly illegally negotiated through banks
run by deposed Knoxville, Tenn., bankers Jake Butcher and C.H.
Butcher Jr.
   Ford's trial is set for Feb. 12.
