<FIRST>r a AM-FurProtests     10-21 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fur Protests,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists in Four States Protest Fur Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CS1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Animal rights activists in Ohio, Kentucky, Maryland and
Minnesota staged protests at department stores Saturday against the
sale of furs.
   Pickets stood outside Lazarus department stores in Columbus,
Ohio, Cincinnati and Louisville, Ky., handing out fliers and copies
of a letter from Lazarus officials declining to take a stand.
   A protest was also held at Higbee's stores in Cleveland and at a
Hutzler's in Baltimore. Two Minneapolis stores _ a Saks Fifth
Avenue and a Dayton-Hudson Corp. outlet _ were also the target of
demonstrators.
   In Columbus, Robin Russell, head of the group Protect Our
Earth's Treasures, suggested the stores could sell fake furs and
still satisfy their customers.
   ``What we found out was that this Lazarus had taken their furs
out a couple months ago because of low sales,'' Russell said. ``But
that reinforces what we are asking even more: Furs are not a large
part of their sales, and it's not going to hurt Lazarus to take the
furs out of their stores.''
   The demonstrators passed out a flier showing a copy of a letter
Daniel G. Bukey, Lazarus' vice president for consumer relations,
wrote to an animal rights group. He said the company ``found it
impractical to make moral, religious and political judgments about
products or the companies that manufacture them. We simply must buy
and sell the merchandise on the merit of the merchandise itself.''
</TEXT>
