<HEAD>Former Federal Reserve President Dead at 79</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW CANAAN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alfred Hayes, the former president of
the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, died Saturday at his home. He
was 79.
   Hayes suffered from Alzheimer's disease and Parkinson's disease
and had been in a nursing home for about four years, said Richard
Hoenig, a spokesman for the bank.
   Hayes was educated at Harvard and Yale universities. He returned
to New York City in 1933 after a year in England as a Rhodes
scholar and started working in the bond department at the National
City Bank of New York, which later became Citibank.
   In 1956, he was appointed to the Federal Reserve and served
there until 1975. During the same period, he was vice chairman of
the Federal Open Market Committee.
