<FIRST>r a AM-DC-10Crash-Parts     10-21 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-10 Crash-Parts,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Parts Found in Farm Fields, GE Says Searches Will End Sunday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALTA, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Volunteers searching northwest Iowa farm
fields Saturday found more parts from an engine of a DC-10 that
crashed July 19, but the key part has failed to turn up,
authorities said.
   The search by 90 volunteers, paid for by General Electric
Aircraft Engines, was to be discontinued Sunday, but rewards still
will be given for significant discoveries.
   Jerry Clark, a GE representative, said search parties using
metal detectors would try one last time to find a flange that
connected the forward fan shaft to the disc in the tail-mounted GE
engine and was held together with 20 bolts.
   The No. 2 engine flew apart as United Flight 232 was flying
north of Alta, spewing metal and severing hydraulic lines for
flight controls. Pilots wrestled the jumbo jet to the Sioux Gateway
Airport in Sioux City but the plane cartwheeled down the runway in
a fiery crash that killed 112 of the 296 people aboard.
   Of the engine pieces still missing, Clark said the flange is the
``thing most important'' to investigators.
   Nick Droegmiller, a farmer near Alta, said volunteers scoured
the fields on his land and found a variety of fragments.
   ``They came up with a couple of retainer pins and an oil line
with what looked like a pump on the end of it,'' he said. Searchers
said it was apparently part of the hydraulic system of the DC-10.
   The company has offered more than $270,000 in rewards for the
return of various parts.
   The largest single award of $119,000 was claimed this month when
Droegmiller's neighbor, farmer Janice Sorenson, found most of the
rear engine fan disc. The rest of the disc was found on the nearby
farm of Harold Halverson, who received about $40,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
