<DOCNO> AP891021-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 2219EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary-West     10-21 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-West,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian Official Wants Soviet Forces Out; Trade With West</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary's foreign minister on Saturday said
Soviet forces should quickly leave his country and that Hungary may
someday join the European Economic Community.
   Foreign Minister Gyula Horn, on a two-day official visit to
Norway, Friday discussed historic reforms in his East bloc nation
with Norway's prime minister, Jan P. Syse. On Saturday, he met with
Foreign Minister Kjell Magne Bondevik.
   ``As soon as possible, Soviet forces should be pulled out of
Hungarian territory. It depends on the success of talks in Vienna
in 1990 about conventional disarmament ... which should give the
green light to the withdrawal,'' Horn said at a news conference.
   About 62,000 Soviet soldiers are stationed in Hungary. The
Soviets have pledged to pull out 10,000 of them by the end of next
year as part of a withdrawal from Eastern Europe.
   Horn also proposed a draft agreement of cooperation with the
six-nation European Free Trade Association to pave the way for
future Hungarian membership.
   He said Hungary may join Western European nations in the
European Economic Community in 10 to 15 years. The EEC, which is
promoting a common European market by 1992, now has 12 members.
   Meanwhile, Horn said, it would be more realistic for Hungary to
seek cooperation with the trade association.
   He said economic reform and trade are as important to
debt-ridden Hungary as political reform. He said the West must help
bolster Hungary's economy.
   ``Development of a political system is something that Hungary
itself decides. Economic development depends on our will and the
West's will,'' he said.
   Hungary this month rewrote its constitution to reflect
democratic ideals, allowing opposition parties and preparing for
its first free elections in 41 years. The elections are to be held
early next year.
   The Communist Party also dissolved itself and formed the
Hungarian Socialist Party, which is headed by reformers.
   ``Hungary is beginning to near the democracy of Western
Europe,'' Horn said. He predicted that the new party, which now
rules the country, will be part of a governing coalition after
multiparty elections.
</TEXT>
