<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 2339EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SheriffSentencing     10-21 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sheriff Sentencing,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheriff Given Suspended Sentenced Fatal Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deputy sheriff who fatally shot his
girlfriend was given a suspended sentence by a judge who said that
``sometimes the commission of the crime is the punishment itself.''
   Alexander G. Costeines, 21, of Shelton, who had been charged
with first-degree manslaughter, bowed his head and sobbed during
the proceedings before Judge Joseph T. Gormley Jr.
   New Haven police charged Costeines, a deputy sheriff in
Bridgeport, hours after the June 3 shooting.
   Costeines and Luanne Dietz, 19, had been sitting in her car that
night when the gun went off. Police and prosecutors said they
believed the shooting was accidental, but also believed Costeines
had lied about some of the details.
   During the trial, Miss Dietz's mother, Mary E. LaMere, told the
judge that nothing would be gained by sending Costeines to prison.
   ``I expect Alex to be accountable for what happened,'' LaMere
said, ``but I don't expect him to be persecuted for something that
didn't happen that way. He was negligent, yes. Did he intend to
hurt her? No.''
   The judge agreed.
   ``Sometimes the commission of the crime is the punishment
itself,'' Gormley said. ``I think in this case, that's absolutely
true.''
   Gormley prohibited Costeines from carrying a weapon for the five
years he will be on probation.
   The gun used in the shooting was Costeines' service revolver.
</TEXT>
