<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS typo in Pulitzer's name; restores headlines. ADDS Hayes.
A separate on Hayes moved as a0680.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Samuel Pulitzer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Samuel Clarence Pulitzer, who grew up in an
orphanage and became a major necktie manufacturer, died of cancer
Friday. He was 84.
   Pulitzer was chief executive officer of WEMCO Inc., a
multimillion-dollar neckwear and sportswear company which makes
ties for such internationally known designers as Oscar de la Renta.
   Pulitzer, who came from a New Orleans family with 11 children,
was placed in the orphanage when he was 6.
   He and his brother, the late Emanuel S. Pulitzer, began working
together in 1925, driving back roads from Texas to Alabama to sell
neckties. Their rise to riches began in 1936, when Samuel Pulitzer
cut up the jacket of his brother's new suit to make a necktie. The
suit was made from a wrinkle-resistant fabric made in England. Ties
made from the cloth quickly became popular.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Melba Allen</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Melba Till Allen, a former state auditor
and state treasurer who was convicted of using her office for
personal gain, died Friday after an 18-year battle with cancer. She
was 56.
   Mrs. Allen was once one of Alabama's most popular politicians.
She was auditor from 1967 to 1975 and treasurer from 1975 to 1978,
when she ran afoul of the law.
   She was convicted of using her office as treasurer to obtain
bank loans to build a theme park and of failing to make full
disclosure of her personal finances, as required by the ethics law.
   Mrs. Allen, who denied any wrongdoing, was sentenced to six
years in jail and 3{ years probation. She spent 30 days in jail and
the rest of her sentence living and working as a bookkeeper at a
Montgomery retirement home.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Milet Andrejevic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Milet Andrejevic, a painter and teacher whose
work is in the permanent collections of such museums as the
Metropolitan Museum of Art and the Whitney Museum of American Art,
died of lung cancer Friday. He was 64.
   Andrejevic, who was considered a member of the Realist school,
had taught painting at the New York Academy of Art since 1985. He
also taught at Brooklyn College and New York University.
   A native of Yugoslavia, he became a U.S. citizen in 1961.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Pearl Izenzon</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pearl Izenzon, who co-founded the Potsmokers
Anonymous drug recovery program, died Friday of cancer. She was 48.
   In 1974, the native New Yorker and her husband, David, created
Potsmokers Anonymous, which was patterned after Alcoholics
Anonymous, to help marijuana users quit. Thousands joined the
program.
   David Izenzon, an artist and musician, died in 1977. Following
his death, Mrs. Izenzon was executive director of Potsmokers
Anonymous.
</TEXT>
