<DOCNO> AP891021-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-21-89 2352EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Relief 2ndLd-Writethru a0671 10-21 0788</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Relief, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0671,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bay Area Relief Donations Focus on Life's Basic Necessities</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 16th graf pvs, `In Montgomery...a day,'
to UPDATE with $60,000 donated at college football game. Pick up 17th graf
pvs: `Greyhound Lines...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HIRSH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans sent planeloads of Pampers, shovels, stoves and other
basic goods to help quake victims rebuild their lives from the
ground up, and relief groups begged for cash to defray what could
prove the costliest U.S. natural disaster.
   Money was donated in every denomination, from children's pennies
to $1 million-plus corporate checks. In quake-conscious Japan,
companies, citizens' groups and local governments pledged hundreds
of thousands of dollars.
   ``The response to the need has been phenomenal,'' Capt. Don
McDougald of the Salvation Army in San Francisco said Saturday.
   ``We are finding material coming from all over the country.
Phoenix has sent six planeloads. States like Texas, Oregon and
Colorado have sent clothing, canned goods and tents of all kinds.''
   In some hard-hit communities near the quake's epicenter, like
Santa Cruz and Watsonville, residents were reduced to a
frontier-like existence, living on donated camping equipment,
cooking stoves and Sterno fuel, McDougald said.
   ``One of the things asked for is pet food. Up in the Santa Cruz
mountains these people keep all kinds of animals,'' McDougald said.
``We also need personal items like toothpaste, brushes and
deodorant.''
   Wet weather Saturday drove more of the newly homeless into some
of the 20 Red Cross shelters housing about 5,000 quake-displaced
people in the San Francisco Bay area.
   ``Our main needs are for cash donations rather than donations of
food or clothing,'' said Red Cross spokesman Bob Howard in Los
Angeles. Most of the money will be used immediately to relocate the
homeless into temporary living quarters, officials said.
   ``With the rain over the next couple of days, people that have
been living outside their homes are going to need to come inside,
so we expect the shelter population to go up considerably,'' Howard
said.
   Since the quake struck Tuesday, the Red Cross alone has received
more than $8 million from individuals and from corporations, many
of them multinationals with ties to the Bay area.
   In quake-sensitive Southern California, people waited in line
for hours to give blood, and former President Reagan phoned in a
$5,000 donation to the Red Cross and recorded a public service
announcement before leaving on his $2 million junket to Japan.
   Orange County schools contributed more than $7,000 to
earthquake-relief efforts, most raised by students and teachers
passing the hat.
   First- and second-graders at Tierra Vista School in Oxnard
decided that the $60 they raised in a recycling drive for crayons,
felt pens and chalk for their classrooms should go to the Red Cross
for earthquake relief.
   Fullerton-based HomeClub Inc., a chain of home improvement
stores, donated about 200 shovels, 600 trash cans and 2,500 canvas
gloves to the Salvation Army.
   Elsewhere around the country, St. Louis-based Anheuser-Busch
Inc., as part of a $2 million donation, sent a trailer-load of
casual wear, including sweatsuits and light jackets. Transportation
was provided free by Union Pacific railroad. Johnson &amp; Johnson
Inc., based in New Brunswick, N.J., shipped in caseloads of
Pampers, the Red Cross said.
   In Montgomery, Ala., the Alabama Baptist State Convention on
Saturday dispatched a disaster relief truck _ actually a giant
kitchen on wheels _ to Santa Cruz, where it is expected to feed up
to 5,000 people a day.
   In Provo, Utah, fans at a football game between Brigham Young
University and the University of Texas-El Paso poured $60,301 into
collection boxes set up for earthquake relief donations to the Red
Cross. That included $20,000 from Joe Cannon, president of Geneva
Steel, who once worked for a steel plant in the San Francisco Bay
area.
   Greyhound Lines Inc. announced Saturday that it is providing
free shipping from seven Western states for emergency relief
supplies being collected by the Salvation Army and American Red
Cross.
   In Japan, where memories of the 1923 earthquake that destroyed
Tokyo are still vivid, the California temblor has aroused
widespread sympathy. Sumitomo Bank and Toyota Motor Corp.'s U.S.
subsidiary each said it was donating $500,000.
   The city of Tokyo sent $15,000 each to San Francisco and
Oakland, Foreign Ministry spokesman Taizo Watanabe said Friday. In
addition, U.S. Kawasaki Motors donated $50,000 in power-generating
equipment.
   Damage estimates for the quake stood at $5.5 billion Saturday
and, by one estimate, could go as high as $10 billion. That would
make it the most expensive natural disaster in U.S. history with
the possible exception of San Francisco's 1906 quake, according to
the Independent Insurance Agents of America, a trade group based in
Washington.
</TEXT>
